[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Presidential elections were held in the United States on November 2, 2004.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Incumbent Republican president George W.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bush and his running mate, incumbent vice president Dick Cheney, were elected to a second term.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] They narrowly defeated the Democratic ticket of Massachusetts junior senator John Kerry and North Carolina senior senator John Edwards.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bush and Cheney were re-nominated by their party with no difficulty.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Meanwhile, the Democrats engaged in a competitive primary.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Kerry emerged as the early front-runner but was faced with serious opposition by former Vermont governor Howard Dean, who briefly surged ahead of Kerry in the polls.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Kerry won the first set of primaries in January and re-emerged as the front-runner, and Dean dropped out in February.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Kerry clinched his party's nomination in March after a series of primary victories over runner-up Edwards, whom he ultimately selected to be his running mate.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The September 11 attacks in 2001 decisively reshaped Bush's foreign policy goals and garnered him near-universal support early in his term.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] However, by 2004 his management of the war on terror attracted serious debate, particularly over his handling of the 2003 invasion of Iraq.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bush presented himself as a decisive leader and attacked Kerry as a "flip-flopper"; Kerry had voted to authorize the invasion, but criticized Bush's conduct of the Iraq War.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Domestic issues were debated as well, including the economy and jobs, health care, abortion, same-sex marriage, and embryonic stem cell research.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bush won by a narrow margin of 35 electoral votes and took 50.7% of the popular vote.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bush swept the South and the Mountain states and took the crucial swing states of Ohio, Iowa, and New Mexico, the last two flipping Republican.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Although Kerry flipped New Hampshire, Bush won both more electoral votes and states than in 2000.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Ohio was the tipping-point state, and was considered to be the state that allowed Bush to win reelection.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Some aspects of the election process were subject to controversy, although not to the degree seen in the 2000 presidential election.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bush won Florida by a 5% margin, a significant improvement over his razor-thin victory margin in the state four years earlier that had led to a legal challenge in *Bush v.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] This remains the most recent presidential election in which the Republican candidate won Colorado, New Mexico, and Virginia.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] At the time, Bush received the most popular votes in history, a record that would be broken in 2008.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bush's win was the only Republican popular vote victory during the eight elections from 1992 to 2020.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bush is the only incumbent Republican president to have won a second term since Ronald Reagan in 1984, and the only Republican presidential candidate to have won a majority of the popular vote since his father in 1988.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bush won the presidency in 2000 after the U.S.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Gore* remanded the case to the Florida Supreme Court, which declared there was not sufficient time to hold a recount without violating the U.S.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Just eight months into Bush's presidency, the terrorist attacks of September 11, 2001, suddenly transformed him into a wartime president.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] His approval ratings surged to near 90%.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Within a month, the forces of a coalition led by the United States entered Afghanistan, which had been sheltering Osama bin Laden, suspected mastermind of the September 11 attacks.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Taliban had been removed by December, although a long reconstruction would follow.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Bush administration then turned its attention to Iraq and argued the need to remove Saddam Hussein from power in Iraq had become urgent.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Among the stated reasons were that Saddam's regime had tried to acquire nuclear material and had not properly accounted for biological and chemical material it was known to have previously possessed.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Both the possession of these weapons of mass destruction (WMD), and the failure to account for them, would violate the UN sanctions.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The assertion about WMD was hotly advanced by the Bush administration from the beginning, but other major powers including China, France, Germany, and Russia remained unconvinced that Iraq was a threat and refused to allow passage of a UN Security Council resolution to authorize the use of force.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Iraq permitted UN weapon inspectors in November 2002, who were continuing their work to assess the WMD claim when the Bush administration decided to proceed with war without UN authorization and told the inspectors to leave the country.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The United States invaded Iraq on March 20, 2003, along with a "coalition of the willing" that consisted of additional troops from the United Kingdom, and to a lesser extent, from Australia and Poland.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Within about three weeks, the invasion caused the collapse of both the Iraqi government and its armed forces; however, the U.S. and allied forces failed to find any weapon of mass destruction in Iraq.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Nevertheless, on May 1, Bush landed on the aircraft carrier USS *Abraham Lincoln*, in a Lockheed S-3 Viking, where he gave a speech announcing the end of "major combat operations" in the Iraq War.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Both candidates were not only graduates of Yale University, but both were also members of the exclusive Skull and Bones society.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] It is the only time two "Bonesmen" have faced each other for the presidency.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bush was able to ward off any serious challenge to the Republican nomination.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Senator Lincoln Chafee from Rhode Island considered challenging Bush on an anti-war platform in New Hampshire but decided not to run after the capture of Saddam Hussein in December 2003.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] On March 10, 2004, Bush officially attained the number of delegates needed to be nominated at the 2004 Republican National Convention in New York City.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He accepted the nomination on September 2, 2004, and retained Vice President Dick Cheney as his running mate.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] During the convention and throughout the campaign, Bush focused on two themes: defending America against terrorism and building an ownership society.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The ownership society included allowing people to invest some of their Social Security in the stock market, increasing home and stock ownership, and encouraging more people to buy their own health insurance.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The 2004 Democratic Party presidential primaries took place from January 14 to June 8, 2004, to select the Democratic Party's nominee for president.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Before the primaries, Vermont governor Howard Dean was a favorite to win the nomination; however, Massachusetts senator John Kerry won victories in two early races: the Iowa caucuses and the New Hampshire primary.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] These wins strengthened Kerry's previously weak campaign.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] By March 11, Kerry had received enough delegates to win the nomination.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Other major candidates included North Carolina senator John Edwards and retired U.S.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Kerry asked Republican senator John McCain to be his running mate but McCain turned down his offer.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] On July 6, Kerry selected Edwards as his running mate, shortly before the 2004 Democratic National Convention was held later that month in Boston.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Heading into the convention, the Kerry–Edwards ticket unveiled its new slogan: a promise to make America "stronger at home and more respected in the world".
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Kerry made his Vietnam War experience the convention's prominent theme.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The keynote address at the convention was delivered by Illinois state senator and U.S.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Senate candidate and future president Barack Obama; the speech was well received, and it elevated Obama's status within the Democratic Party.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] There were four other presidential tickets on the ballot in a number of states totaling enough electoral votes to have a theoretical possibility of winning a majority in the Electoral College.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Ahead of the 2004 election, some states implemented electronic voting systems.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Critics raised several issues about voting machines, particularly those made by Diebold Election Systems.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Cybersecurity professionals found security vulnerabilities in Diebold machines.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Voting machines made by several companies were also criticized for their lack of a paper trail, which would have made results easier to verify.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Democrats also criticized various executives at Diebold, Inc.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] (the parent company of Diebold Election Systems) for their support of Bush's campaign, stating that it constituted a conflict of interest.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Following these issues, California banned the use of Diebold's AccuVote TSX voting machines for elections in 2004.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The 2004 election was the first to be affected by the campaign finance reforms mandated by the Bipartisan Campaign Reform Act of 2002.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The act created restrictions on fundraising by political parties and candidates.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] A large number of independent 527 groups were created to bypass these restrictions.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Named for a section of the Internal Revenue Code, these groups were able to raise large amounts of money for various political causes as long as they did not coordinate their activities with political campaigns.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Examples of 527s include Swift Boat Veterans for Truth, MoveOn.org, the Media Fund, and America Coming Together.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] These groups were active throughout the campaign season, spending a record $556 million for all elections in 2004.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Stand by Your Ad provision of the Bipartisan Campaign Reform Act required political advertisements on television to include a verbal disclaimer identifying the organization or campaign responsible for the advertisement.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] This provision was intended to force campaigns to take responsibility for negative advertisements.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Campaign strategists criticized this requirement, stating that it would waste time and cause voters to be confused.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Kerry's campaign managers believed that Kerry had an advantage on domestic issues.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bush's campaign also focused on increasing voter turnout among conservatives.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] According to one exit poll, people who voted for Bush cited the issues of terrorism and traditional values as the most important factors in their decision.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Kerry supporters cited the war in Iraq, the economy and jobs, and health care.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Tax cuts were passed in 2001 and 2003 under the Bush administration with Bush's support.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] During the 2004 campaign, Bush praised these tax cuts, stating that they helped to grow the economy.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] On the other hand, Kerry attacked Bush for failing to create jobs under his presidency.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Kerry stated that he wanted to reduce the United States budget deficit by capping government spending while ending various tax breaks for businesses.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Kerry also supported tax credits for businesses that hire additional workers.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bush attacked Kerry for his economic proposals, stating that they would cause Americans to pay higher taxes.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bush also attacked Kerry for previously supporting tax raises, such as a proposed increase on the federal gas tax.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bush defended the Iraq War, arguing that it was necessary to stop terrorism.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He also said that the United States had made progress stopping terrorism in other nations.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bush attacked Kerry for opposing the Iraq War after voting to authorize it in 2002, characterizing the shift as one of many flip-flops by Kerry.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Kerry argued that Bush had misled the American public in pursuing the Iraq War, noting that no illegal weapons had been found in Iraq.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He said that the Iraq War was a mistake and a diversion from terrorism in other nations such as Afghanistan.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] After the election, exit polls found that foreign policy concerns were the most important issues for voters.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Health savings accounts (HSAs) were introduced in 2004 as part of the Medicare Prescription Drug, Improvement, and Modernization Act, signed by Bush in December 2003.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] As part of his 2004 campaign, Bush supported the expansion of HSAs.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He proposed tax cuts to help Americans purchase their own health insurance.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] He also proposed a plan that would allow small businesses to purchase health insurance in large groups.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Kerry's health care proposals included government subsidies for businesses that provide health insurance and the expansion of government-run health care programs.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Health policy experts stated that Bush's proposals would have a more limited impact than Kerry's proposals.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Kerry also attacked Bush for his policy on stem cell research.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In 2001, the Bush administration restricted embryonic stem cell research to existing stem cell lines.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Kerry stated that this restriction was a barrier to conducting important research.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In July 2004, Bush announced his support for a Constitutional amendment to ban same-sex marriage, shortly before the Senate voted on the amendment.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Although Kerry stated that he opposed same-sex marriage, he also opposed the amendment, saying that the legality of same-sex marriage should be decided by individual states.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] During the campaign, Bush was accused of failing to fulfill his required service in the Texas Air National Guard.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] A scandal occurred at CBS News after they aired a segment on *60 Minutes Wednesday*, introducing what became known as the Killian documents.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] These documents were allegedly written by Jerry B.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Killian, Bush's squadron commander, and they contained various allegations about Bush's service.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Serious doubts about the documents' authenticity quickly emerged, leading CBS to appoint a review panel that eventually resulted in the firing of the news producer and other significant staffing changes.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Killian documents were eventually concluded to be forgeries.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Kerry was accused by the Swift Vets and POWs for Truth of distorting his military service in Vietnam.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The group challenged the legitimacy of each of the combat medals awarded to Kerry by the U.S.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Navy, and the disposition of his discharge.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The organization spent $22.4 million in advertisements against Kerry.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] After the election, political analysts described their advertising campaign as effective.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The term swiftboating was used during the campaign to describe the organization's negative advertising, which Democrats saw as unfair.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] It was also used after the campaign to generally describe a harsh attack by a political opponent that is dishonest, personal and unfair.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Three presidential debates and one vice presidential debate were organized by the Commission on Presidential Debates, and held in the autumn of 2004.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] On October 29, four days before the election, excerpts of a video of Osama bin Laden addressing the American people were broadcast on al Jazeera.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In his remarks, bin Laden mentions the September 11 attacks, and taunted Bush over his response to them.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In the days following the video's release, Bush's lead over Kerry increased by several points.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Elections analysts and political pundits issue probabilistic forecasts of the composition of the Electoral College.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] These forecasts use a variety of factors to estimate the likelihood of each candidate winning the Electoral College electors for that state.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Below is a list of states considered by one or more forecasts to be competitive; states that are not deemed to be "safe" or "solid" by at least one of the forecasters *The Cook Political Report*, *The New York Times*, and CNN.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] (a) *One faithless elector from Minnesota cast an electoral vote for John Edwards (written as John Ewards) for president.* (b) *In Montana, Karen Sanchirico was listed on the ballot as Nader's running mate, not Camejo.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In New York, Nader appeared on two distinct tickets, one with Camejo and one with Pierce.* (c) *Because Arrin Hawkins, then aged 28, was constitutionally ineligible to serve as vice president, Margaret Trowe replaced her on the ballot in some states.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Of the 3,154 counties/districts/independent cities making returns, Bush won the popular vote in 2,568 (81.42%) while Kerry carried 586 (18.58%).
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The following table records the official vote tallies for each state as reported by the official Federal Election Commission report.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The column labeled "Margin" shows Bush's margin of victory over Kerry (the margin is negative for states and districts won by Kerry).
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Although Guam has no votes in the Electoral College, it has held a straw poll for its presidential preference since 1980.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Maine and Nebraska each allowed for their electoral votes to be split between candidates.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In both states, two electoral votes were awarded to the winner of the statewide race and one electoral vote was awarded to the winner of each congressional district.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Red font color denotes those won by Republican President George W.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bush; blue denotes states won by Democrat John Kerry.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] One elector in Minnesota cast a ballot for president with the name of "John Ewards" [*sic*] written on it.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The Electoral College officials certified this ballot as a vote for Edwards for president.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The remaining nine electors cast ballots for Kerry.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] All ten electors in the state cast ballots for Edwards for vice president (Edwards's name was spelled correctly on all ballots for vice president).
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] This was the first time in U.S. history that an elector had cast a vote for the same person to be both president and vice president.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Electoral balloting in Minnesota was performed by secret ballot, and none of the electors admitted to casting the Edwards vote for president, so it may never be known who the faithless elector was.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] It is not even known whether the vote for Edwards was deliberate or unintentional; the Republican Secretary of State and several of the Democratic electors have expressed the opinion that this was an accident.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] During the campaign and as the results came in on the night of the election, there was much focus on Ohio, Pennsylvania, and Florida.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] These three swing states were seen as evenly divided, and with each casting 20 electoral votes or more, they had the power to decide the election.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] As the final results came in, Kerry took Pennsylvania and then Bush took Florida, focusing all attention on Ohio.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The morning after the election, the winner was still undetermined.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The result in Ohio would decide the winner, although the results in New Mexico and Iowa were also undetermined.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bush led in Ohio, but the state was still counting provisional ballots.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In the afternoon of the day after the election, Ohio Secretary of State Ken Blackwell announced that there were roughly 135,000 provisional ballots remaining.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Kerry's campaign believed that it was statistically impossible to erase Bush's lead.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Faced with this announcement, Kerry conceded defeat.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bush became the first Republican to ever win without carrying New Hampshire, and the first to win the popular vote without Vermont and Illinois.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] This was the last time a president was re-elected to a consecutive term with a higher share of the electoral or popular vote.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bush carried Colorado despite the state being Kerry's birth state.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bush simultaneously lost his own birth state of Connecticut, making this the only election since 1864 where neither candidate carried their birth state.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] This election was the first time since 1976 that New Jersey, Connecticut, Vermont, Maine, Illinois, Michigan, and California voted for the losing candidate in the popular vote, the first time since 1980 that Maryland did so, and the first time since 1948 that Delaware did so.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bush's 2.4% popular vote margin is the smallest ever for a re-elected incumbent president, surpassing the 1812 election.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bush won three states that have not voted Republican since: Virginia, Colorado, and New Mexico.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Virginia had voted Republican in every election from 1968 to 2004 but conversely has voted Democratic in every election since 2008.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In contrast, this is the last election in which the losing candidate won any of the following states: Michigan, Pennsylvania, and Wisconsin.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] This is also the last time a Republican was elected without carrying Maine's 2nd congressional district.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] This election is the only time in history that every Northeastern state voted Democratic and every former Confederate state voted Republican in the same election.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Thus, Bush is the only candidate to win without carrying any Northeastern electoral votes.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Furthermore, this was the last election where both major party tickets consisted entirely of white men.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] This is also the most recent election that the incumbent party would flip any states, with Bush becoming the first Republican since 1984 to win the state of Iowa, and since 1988 to win the state of New Mexico, both states he did not win in 2000.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] This was the last election where Nevada voted Republican until 2024; and Florida, Iowa, and Ohio until 2016.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] This is the only presidential election since 1988 in which a Republican nominee won the national popular vote with a majority, and it remains the only presidential election since 1984 in which an incumbent Republican president won a second consecutive term.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bush became the only incumbent president to win consecutive re-election after previously losing the popular vote.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bush was also the first of only two presidents to win the Electoral College while losing the popular vote in a previous election but later winning both the Electoral College and the popular vote in a subsequent election.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bush is the seventh Republican to have won re-election to a consecutive term, along with Abraham Lincoln, Ulysses S.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Eisenhower, Richard Nixon, and Ronald Reagan.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] Bush was also the last Republican to win a second term in the White House until Donald Trump in 2024.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] The 2004 election had the highest turnout rate among eligible voters since 1968.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] This was the first presidential election since 1988 where a candidate won a majority of the popular vote.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] This was the last time a Republican nominee won the national popular vote until Donald Trump in 2024.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] This remains the most recent presidential election in which both major party candidates flipped at least one state.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] In addition, this was one of only two elections in the 21st century in which a candidate from either party won fewer than 20 states, with the other being 2024, when Kamala Harris won 19 states, the same as John Kerry.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] This is the most recent instance in which both major party tickets did not include a woman or a person of color.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] This, along with the previous election would be the only ones between 1980 and 2024 where the winner won fewer than 300 electoral votes (or below 55% of the electoral college vote).
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p01] This is also the last winning ticket that did not have Joe Biden or Donald Trump on it.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p02] In 2004, voters with and without college degrees were roughly evenly split along partisan lines.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p02] By 2024, voters with college degrees were Democratic-leaning, while voters without college degrees were Republican-leaning.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p02] After the election, activists and election scholars criticized various issues with the election in Ohio.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Long lines at polling places over seven hours were reported.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p02] An electronic voting machine erroneously gave thousands of extra votes to Bush.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Foley stated that he believed that Ohio's voting problems did not affect the outcome.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p02] After the election, many blogs published false rumors claiming to show evidence that voter fraud had prevented Kerry from winning.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Although the overall result of the election was not challenged by the Kerry campaign, Green Party presidential candidate David Cobb and Libertarian Party presidential candidate Michael Badnarik obtained a recount in Ohio.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p02] This recount was completed December 28, 2004, although on January 24, 2007, a jury convicted two Ohio elections officials of selecting precincts to recount where they already knew the hand total would match the machine total, thereby avoiding having to perform a full recount.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Independent candidate Ralph Nader obtained a recount in 11 New Hampshire precincts that used Accuvote voting machines.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p02] At the official counting of the electoral votes on January 6, an objection was made under the Electoral Count Act (now 3 U.S.C. § 15) to Ohio's electoral votes.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Because the motion was supported by at least one member of both the House of Representatives and the Senate, the law required that the two houses separate to debate and vote on the objection.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p02] In the House of Representatives, the objection was supported by 31 Democrats.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p02] It was opposed by 178 Republicans, 88 Democrats and one independent.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Not voting were 52 Republicans and 80 Democrats.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Four people elected to the House had not yet taken office, and one seat was vacant.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p02] In the Senate, it was supported only by its maker, Barbara Boxer, with 74 senators opposed and 25 not voting.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p02] During the debate, no Senator argued that the outcome of the election should be changed by either court challenge or revote.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Boxer claimed that she had made the motion not to challenge the outcome but "to cast the light of truth on a flawed system which must be fixed now".
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p02] Kerry would later state that "the widespread irregularities make it impossible to know for certain that the [Ohio] outcome reflected the will of the voters".
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p02] In the same article, Democratic National Committee Chairman Howard Dean said: "I'm not confident that the election in Ohio was fairly decided...
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p02] We know that there was substantial voter suppression, and the machines were not reliable.
[src:false-color/2004-united-states-presidential-election-p02] It should not be a surprise that the Republicans are willing to do things that are unethical to manipulate elections.
[src:false-color/achromatopsia] The syndrome is typically first noticed in children around six months of age due to their photophobia or their nystagmus.
[src:false-color/achromatopsia] The nystagmus becomes less noticeable with age but the other symptoms of the syndrome become more relevant as school age approaches.
[src:false-color/achromatopsia] Visual acuity and stability of the eye motions generally improve during the first six to seven years of life – but remain near 20/200.
[src:false-color/achromatopsia] Otherwise the syndrome is considered stationary and does not worsen with age.
[src:false-color/achromatopsia] If the light level during testing is optimized, achromats may achieve corrected visual acuity of 20/100 to 20/150 at lower light levels, regardless of the absence of color.
[src:false-color/achromatopsia] The fundus of the eye appears completely normal.
[src:false-color/achromatopsia] Achromatopsia can be classified as *complete* or *incomplete*.
[src:false-color/achromatopsia] In general, symptoms of incomplete achromatopsia are attenuated versions of those of complete achromatopsia.
[src:false-color/achromatopsia] Individuals with incomplete achromatopsia have reduced visual acuity with or without nystagmus or photophobia.
[src:false-color/achromatopsia] Incomplete achromats show only partial impairment of cone cell function.
[src:false-color/achromatopsia] Achromatopsia is sometimes called **rod monochromacy** (as opposed to blue cone monochromacy), as achromats exhibit a complete absence of cone cell activity via electroretinography in photopic lighting.
[src:false-color/achromatopsia] The hemeralopic aspect of achromatopsia can be diagnosed non-invasively using electroretinography.
[src:false-color/achromatopsia] The response at low (scotopic) and median (mesopic) light levels will be normal but the response under high light level (photopic) conditions will be absent.
[src:false-color/achromatopsia] The mesopic level is approximately a hundred times lower than the clinical level used for the typical high level electroretinogram.
[src:false-color/achromatopsia] When as described; the condition is due to a saturation in the neural portion of the retina and not due to the absence of the photoreceptors per se.
[src:false-color/achromatopsia] In general, the molecular pathomechanism of achromatopsia is either the inability to properly control or respond to altered levels of cGMP; particularly important in visual perception as its level controls the opening of cyclic nucleotide-gated ion channels (CNGs).
[src:false-color/achromatopsia] Decreasing the concentration of cGMP results in closure of CNGs and resulting hyperpolarization and cessation of glutamate release.
[src:false-color/achromatopsia] Native retinal CNGs are composed of 2 α- and 2 β-subunits, which are CNGA3 and CNGB3, respectively, in cone cells.
[src:false-color/achromatopsia] When expressed alone, CNGB3 cannot produce functional channels, whereas this is not the case for CNGA3.
[src:false-color/achromatopsia] Coassembly of CNGA3 and CNGB3 produces channels with altered membrane expression, ion permeability (Na+ vs.
[src:false-color/achromatopsia] K+ and Ca2+), relative efficacy of cAMP/cGMP activation, decreased outward rectification, current flickering, and sensitivity to block by L-cis-diltiazem.
[src:false-color/achromatopsia] Mutations tend to result in the loss of CNGB3 function or gain of function—often increased affinity for cGMP—of CNGA3. cGMP levels are controlled by the activity of the cone cell transducin, GNAT2.
[src:false-color/achromatopsia] Mutations in GNAT2 tend to result in a truncated and, presumably, non-functional protein, thereby preventing alteration of cGMP levels by photons.
[src:false-color/achromatopsia] There is a positive correlation between the severity of mutations in these proteins and the completeness of the achromatopsia phenotype.
[src:false-color/achromatopsia] Molecular diagnosis can be established by identification of biallelic variants in the causative genes.
[src:false-color/achromatopsia] Molecular genetic testing approaches used in achromatopsia can include targeted analysis for the common CNGB3 variant c.1148delC (p.Thr383IlefsTer13), use of a multigenerational panel, or comprehensive genomic testing.
[src:false-color/achromatopsia] While some mutations in CNGA3 result in truncated and, presumably, non-functional channels this is largely not the case.
[src:false-color/achromatopsia] While few mutations have received in-depth study, at least one mutation does result in functional channels.
[src:false-color/achromatopsia] Curiously, this mutation, T369S, produces profound alterations when expressed without CNGB3.
[src:false-color/achromatopsia] One such alteration is decreased affinity for cyclic guanosine monophosphate.
[src:false-color/achromatopsia] Others include the introduction of a sub-conductance, altered single-channel gating kinetics, and increased calcium permeability.
[src:false-color/achromatopsia] When mutant T369S channels coassemble with CNGB3, however, the only remaining aberration is increased calcium permeability.
[src:false-color/achromatopsia] While it is not immediately clear how this increase in Ca2+ leads to achromatopsia, one hypothesis is that this increased current decreases the signal-to-noise ratio.
[src:false-color/achromatopsia] Other characterized mutations, such as Y181C and the other S1 region mutations, result in decreased current density due to an inability of the channel to traffic to the surface.
[src:false-color/achromatopsia] Such loss of function will undoubtedly negate the cone cell's ability to respond to visual input and produce achromatopsia.
[src:false-color/achromatopsia] At least one other missense mutation outside of the S1 region, T224R, also leads to loss of function.
[src:false-color/achromatopsia] While very few mutations in CNGB3 have been characterized, the vast majority of them result in truncated channels that are presumably non-functional.
[src:false-color/achromatopsia] This will largely result in haploinsufficiency, though in some cases the truncated proteins may be able to coassemble with wild-type channels in a dominant negative fashion.
[src:false-color/achromatopsia] The most prevalent ACHM3 mutation, T383IfsX12, results in a non-functional truncated protein that does not properly traffic to the cell membrane.
[src:false-color/achromatopsia] The three missense mutations that have received further study show a number of aberrant properties, with one underlying theme.
[src:false-color/achromatopsia] The R403Q mutation, which lies in the pore region of the channel, results in an increase in outward current rectification, versus the largely linear current-voltage relationship of wild-type channels, concomitant with an increase in cGMP affinity.
[src:false-color/achromatopsia] The other mutations show either increased (S435F) or decreased (F525N) surface expression but also with increased affinity for cAMP and cGMP.
[src:false-color/achromatopsia] It is the increased affinity for cGMP and cAMP in these mutants that is likely the disorder-causing change.
[src:false-color/achromatopsia] Such increased affinity will result in channels that are insensitive to the slight concentration changes of cGMP due to light input into the retina.
[src:false-color/achromatopsia] Upon activation by light, cone opsin causes the exchange of GDP for GTP in the guanine nucleotide binding protein (G-protein) α-transducing activity polypeptide 2 (GNAT2).
[src:false-color/achromatopsia] This causes the release of the activated α-subunit from the inhibitory β/γ-subunits.
[src:false-color/achromatopsia] This α-subunit then activates a phosphodiesterase that catalyzes the conversion of cGMP to GMP, thereby reducing current through CNG3 channels.
[src:false-color/achromatopsia] As this process is absolutely vital for proper color processing it is not surprising that mutations in GNAT2 lead to achromatopsia.
[src:false-color/achromatopsia] The known mutations in this gene, all result in truncated proteins.
[src:false-color/achromatopsia] Presumably, then, these proteins are non-functional and, consequently, cone opsin that has been activated by light does not lead to altered cGMP levels or photoreceptor membrane hyperpolarization.
[src:false-color/achromatopsia] As achromatopsia is linked to only a few single-gene mutations, it is a good candidate for gene therapy.
[src:false-color/achromatopsia] Gene therapy is a technique for injecting functional genes into the cells that need them, replacing or overruling the original alleles linked to achromatopsia, thereby curing it – at least in part.
[src:false-color/achromatopsia] Achromatopsia has been a focus of gene therapy since 2010, when achromatopsia in dogs was partially cured.
[src:false-color/achromatopsia] Several clinical trials on humans are ongoing with mixed results.
[src:false-color/achromatopsia] In July 2023, a study found positive but limited improvements on congenital CNGA3 achromatopsia.
[src:false-color/achromatopsia] Since 2003, a cybernetic device called the eyeborg has allowed people to perceive color through sound waves.
[src:false-color/achromatopsia] This form of sensory substitution maps the hue perceived by a camera worn on the head to a pitch experienced through bone conduction according to a sonochromatic scale.
[src:false-color/achromatopsia] This allows achromats (or even the totally blind) to perceive – or estimate – the color of an object.
[src:false-color/achromatopsia] Achromat and artist Neil Harbisson was the first to use the eyeborg in early 2004, which allowed him to start painting in color.
[src:false-color/achromatopsia] He has since acted as a spokesperson for the technology, namely in a 2012 TED Talk.
[src:false-color/achromatopsia] A 2015 study suggests that achromats who use the Eyeborg for several years exhibit neural plasticity, which indicates the sensory substitution has become intuitive for them.
[src:false-color/achromatopsia] Achromatopsia is a relatively uncommon disorder, with a prevalence of 1 in 30,000 people.
[src:false-color/achromatopsia] However, on the small Micronesian atoll of Pingelap, approximately five percent of the atoll's 3,000 inhabitants are affected.
[src:false-color/achromatopsia] This is the result of a population bottleneck caused by a typhoon and ensuing famine in the 1770s, which killed all but about twenty islanders, including one who was heterozygous for achromatopsia.
[src:false-color/achromatopsia] The people of this region have termed achromatopsia "maskun", which literally means "not see" in Pingelapese.
[src:false-color/achromatopsia] This unusual population drew neurologist Oliver Sacks to the island for which he wrote his 1997 book, *The Island of the Colorblind*.
[src:false-color/achromatopsia] Blue cone monochromacy (BCM) is another genetic condition causing monochromacy.
[src:false-color/achromatopsia] It mimics many of the symptoms of incomplete achromatopsia and before the discovery of its molecular biological basis was commonly referred to as *x-linked achromatopsia*, *sex-linked achromatopsia* or *atypical achromatopsia*.
[src:false-color/achromatopsia] BCM stems from mutations or deletions of the OPN1LW and OPN1MW genes, both on the X chromosome.
[src:false-color/achromatopsia] As a recessive x-linked condition, BCM disproportionately affects males, unlike typical achromatopsia.
[src:false-color/achromatopsia] Cerebral achromatopsia is a form of acquired color blindness that is caused by damage to the cerebral cortex.
[src:false-color/achromatopsia] Damage is most commonly localized to visual area V4 of the visual cortex (the major part of the colour center), which receives information from the parvocellular pathway involved in color processing.
[src:false-color/achromatopsia] It is most frequently caused by physical trauma, hemorrhage or tumor tissue growth.
[src:false-color/achromatopsia] If there is unilateral damage, a loss of color perception in only half of the visual field may result; this is known as hemiachromatopsia.
[src:false-color/achromatopsia] Cerebral achromats usually do not experience the other major symptoms of congenital achromatopsia, since photopic vision still functions.
[src:false-color/achromatopsia] Color agnosia involves having difficulty recognizing colors, while still being able to perceive them as measured by a color matching or categorizing task.
[src:false-color/achromatopsia] Complete lack of the perception of color in a subject, seeing only in black, white, and shades of grey.
[src:false-color/achromatopsia] Reduced visual capacity in bright light, i.e. day-blindness.
[src:false-color/achromatopsia] Term to describe both normal and pathological conditions related to the oculomotor system.
[src:false-color/achromatopsia] is quite noticeable and the frequency of the oscillation tends to be quite low.
[src:false-color/additive-color] Additive color models are applied in the design and testing of electronic displays that are used to render realistic images containing diverse sets of color using phosphors that emit light of a limited set of primary colors.
[src:false-color/additive-color] Examination with a sufficiently powerful magnifying lens will reveal that each pixel in CRT, LCD, and most other types of color video displays is composed of red, green, and blue light-emitting phosphors which appear as a variety of single colors when viewed from a normal distance.
[src:false-color/additive-color] Additive color, alone, does not predict the appearance of mixtures of printed color inks, dye layers in color photographs on film, or paint mixtures.
[src:false-color/additive-color] Instead, subtractive color is used to model the appearance of pigments or dyes, such as those in paints and inks.
[src:false-color/additive-color] The combination of two of the common three additive primary colors in equal proportions produces an additive secondary color—cyan, magenta or yellow.
[src:false-color/additive-color] Additive color is also used to predict colors from overlapping projected colored lights often used in theatrical lighting for plays, concerts, circus shows, and night clubs.
[src:false-color/additive-color] The full gamut of color available in any additive color system is defined by all the possible combinations of all the possible luminosities of each primary color in that system.
[src:false-color/additive-color] In chromaticity space, a gamut is a plane convex polygon with corners at the primaries.
[src:false-color/additive-color] Systems of additive color are motivated by the Young–Helmholtz theory of trichromatic color vision, which was articulated around 1850 by Hermann von Helmholtz, based on earlier work by Thomas Young.
[src:false-color/additive-color] For his experimental work on the subject, James Clerk Maxwell is sometimes credited as being the father of additive color.
[src:false-color/additive-color] He had the photographer Thomas Sutton photograph a tartan ribbon on black-and-white film three times, first with a red, then green, then blue color filter over the lens.
[src:false-color/additive-color] The three black-and-white images were developed and then projected onto a screen with three different projectors, each equipped with the corresponding red, green, or blue color filter used to take its image.
[src:false-color/additive-color] When brought into alignment, the three images (a black-and-red image, a black-and-green image and a black-and-blue image) formed a full-color image, thus demonstrating the principles of additive color.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Aesthetic properties are features that influence the appeal of objects.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] They include aesthetic values, which express positive or negative qualities, such as the contrast between beauty and ugliness.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Philosophers debate whether aesthetic properties have objective existence or depend on the subjective experiences of observers.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] According to a common view, aesthetic experiences are associated with disinterested pleasure detached from practical concerns.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Taste is a subjective sensitivity to aesthetic qualities, and differences in taste can lead to disagreements about aesthetic judgments.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Artworks are artifacts or performances typically created by humans, encompassing diverse forms such as painting, music, dance, architecture, and literature.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Some definitions focus on their intrinsic aesthetic qualities; others understand art as a socially constructed category.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Art interpretation and criticism seek to identify the meanings of artworks.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Discussions focus on elements such as what an artwork represents, which emotions it expresses, and what the author's underlying intent was.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Many fields of study investigate aesthetic phenomena, examining their roles in ethics, religion, and everyday life, as well as the psychological processes involved in aesthetic experiences.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Comparative aesthetics analyzes the similarities and differences between traditions such as Western, Indian, Chinese, Islamic, and African aesthetics.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Aesthetic thought has its roots in antiquity but only emerged as a distinct field of inquiry in the 18th century when philosophers systematically engaged with the subject.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Aesthetics, sometimes spelled *esthetics*, is the systematic study of beauty, art, and taste.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] As a branch of philosophy, it examines which types of aesthetic phenomena there are, how people experience them, and how objects evoke them.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] This field also investigates the nature of aesthetic judgments, the meaning of artworks, and the problem of art criticism.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Key questions in aesthetics include "What is art?", "Can aesthetic judgments be objective?", and "How is aesthetic value related to other values?".
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] One characterization distinguishes between three main approaches to aesthetics: the study of aesthetic concepts and judgments, the study of aesthetic experiences and other mental responses, and the study of the nature and features of aesthetic objects.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] In a slightly different sense, the term *aesthetics* can also refer to particular theories of beauty or to beautiful appearances.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Aesthetics is closely related to the philosophy of art, and the two terms are often used interchangeably since both involve the philosophical study of aesthetic phenomena.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] One difference is that the philosophy of art focuses on art, whereas the scope of aesthetics also includes other domains, such as beauty in nature and everyday life.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Accordingly, one outlook argues that the philosophy of art is a subfield of aesthetics.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] The precise relation between the two fields is disputed, and another characterization holds that the philosophy of art is the broader discipline.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] This view asserts that aesthetics mainly addresses aesthetic properties, while the philosophy of art also investigates non-aesthetic features of artworks, belonging to fields such as metaphysics, epistemology, philosophy of language, and ethics.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Even though the philosophical study of aesthetic problems originated in antiquity, it was not until the 18th century that aesthetics emerged as a distinct branch of philosophy when philosophers engaged in systematic inquiry into its principles.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] The Latin term *aesthetica* was coined by the philosopher Alexander Baumgarten in 1735, initially defined as the study of sensibility or sensations of beautiful objects.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] The term comes from the ancient Greek words *aisthetikos*, meaning 'perceptible things', *aisthesthai*, meaning 'perceive, see', and *aisthesis*, meaning 'sensation, perception'.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] The earliest known use in the English language appeared in a translation by W.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Philosophers rely on several basic concepts in their inquiry.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] They examine aesthetic objects and the properties or features responsible for their appeal, such as beauty.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Researchers study the experience and pleasure these objects evoke, the judgments about them, and taste as an underlying sensitivity.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] However, this field comes with theoretical difficulties caused by disagreements about the definitions of and relations between these concepts.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Similarly, the exact boundaries of the domain of aesthetics as a whole are disputed—it is controversial whether there is a group of essential features shared by all aesthetic phenomena or whether they are more loosely related through family resemblances.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Aesthetic properties are features of an object that shape its appeal or factors that influence aesthetic evaluations.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] For instance, when an art critic describes an artwork as *great*, *vivid*, or *amusing*, they express aesthetic properties of this artwork.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Some aesthetic properties focus on aesthetic value in general, like *beautiful* and *ugly*; others center on more specific forms of value, such as *graceful* and *elegant*.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Aesthetic properties can also refer to perceptual qualities of objects like *balanced* and *vivid*, to representational aspects like *realistic* and *distorted*, or to emotional responses such as *joyful* and *angry*.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] The precise distinction between aesthetic and non-aesthetic properties is disputed.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] According to one proposal, aesthetic properties require a specific aesthetic sensitivity in addition to the sensory perception of non-aesthetic properties, going beyond simple colors, shapes, and sounds.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Aesthetic properties are associated with evaluations, but not all are intrinsically good or bad.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] For example, being a realistic representation may be aesthetically good in some artistic contexts and bad in others.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] The school of realism argues that aesthetic properties are objective, mind-independent features of reality.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] A related proposal asserts that they are emergent properties dependent on non-aesthetic properties.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] According to this view, the beauty of a painting may emerge from the right combination of colors and shapes.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] A different position holds that aesthetic properties are response-dependent, for example, that features of objects only qualify as aesthetic properties if they evoke aesthetic experiences in observers.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] The terms "aesthetic property" and "aesthetic quality" are often used interchangeably.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Some philosophers distinguish the two, associating aesthetic properties with objective features and aesthetic qualities with subjective experiences and emotional responses.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] An aesthetic object is an object with aesthetic properties.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] One interpretation suggests that aesthetic objects are material entities that evoke aesthetic experiences.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] According to this view, if a person admires an oil painting, then the physical canvas and paint make up the aesthetic object.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Another interpretation, associated with the school of phenomenology, argues that aesthetic objects are not material but intentional objects.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Intentional objects are part of the content of experiences, and their existence depends on the perceiver.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] An intentional object may accurately reflect a material object, as in the case of veridical perceptions, but can also fail to do so, which happens during perceptual illusions.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] The phenomenological perspective focuses on the intentional object given in experience rather than the material object considered independently of the perceiver.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Aesthetic values are a special type of aesthetic property.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] They express the sensory appeal of an object as a qualitative measure of its aesthetic merit, encompassing both positive and negative evaluations.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Aesthetic values contrast with values in other domains, such as moral, epistemic, religious, and economic values.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] The aesthetic value of beauty is often singled out as a central topic of aesthetics.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] It is a key aspect of human experience, influencing both personal decisions and cultural developments.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Often-cited examples of beautiful objects include landscapes, sunsets, humans, and artworks.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] As a positive value, beauty contrasts with ugliness as its negative counterpart.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Beauty is typically understood as a quality of objects that involves balance or harmony and evokes admiration or pleasure when perceived, but its precise definition is debated.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Some theories understand beauty as an objective feature of external objects.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Others emphasize its subjective nature, linking it to personal experience and perception.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] They argue that "beauty is in the eye of the beholder" rather than in the perceived object.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Another central debate concerns the features that all beautiful objects have in common.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] The so-called *classical conception of beauty* is rooted in classical antiquity and the Italian Renaissance.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Focusing on objective features, it asserts that beauty is a harmonious arrangement of parts into a coherent whole.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Aesthetic hedonism, by contrast, is a subjective theory holding that a thing is beautiful if it acts as a source of aesthetic pleasure.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Other conceptions define beautiful objects in terms of intrinsic value, the manifestation of ideal forms, or as what evokes love and passion.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] In pre-modern philosophy, beauty was often treated as the only aesthetic value.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] This outlook holds that beauty encompasses all that is aesthetically commendable and serves as a unifying concept of the whole domain of aesthetics.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] As discussions of aesthetic phenomena expanded, other aesthetic values were proposed.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] For example, the sublime is another value of things that inspire feelings of awe and fear.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Further suggested values include charm, elegance, harmony, and grace.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] An aesthetic experience is an appreciation of beauty or an awareness of other aesthetic features.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] In its most typical form, it is a sensory perception of a natural object or an artwork.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] It can also take other forms, such as aesthetic imagination of fictional objects described in literature.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Internalist theories, like Monroe Beardsley's view, explain aesthetic experience from a first-person perspective, focusing on aspects internal to the experience, such as focus and intensity.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] By contrast, externalist theories, such as George Dickie's position, argue that the key element of aesthetic experiences comes from the perceived external objects and their aesthetic properties.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Several features are associated with aesthetic experiences, but it is controversial whether any of them are essential.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Aesthetic experiences usually appreciate an object for its own sake because of its sensory properties, resulting in aesthetic pleasure from a positive evaluation of the object.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] This pleasure is typically said to be detached from practical concerns and can involve selfless absorption, allowing imaginative freedom or free play of mental faculties in addition to sensory perception.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Some theorists associate this free play with an absence of conceptual activity.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Aesthetic experiences may also be normative, meaning that certain responses are appropriate, like the positive appreciation of beauty, but others are not, such as the positive appreciation of ugliness.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] A central aspect of aesthetic experience is the aesthetic attitude—a special way of observing or engaging with art and nature.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] This attitude involves a form of pure appreciation of perceptual qualities detached from personal desires and practical concerns.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] It is disinterested in this sense by engaging with an object for its own sake without ulterior motives or practical consequences.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] For example, the experience of a violent storm through the aesthetic attitude may focus on its intricate patterns of lightning and thunder rather than preparing for its immediate dangers.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] One characterization understands the aesthetic attitude as a natural form of apprehension that occurs on its own in certain situations.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Another outlook holds that the aesthetic attitude is a voluntary stance people can choose to adopt toward any object.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] There is debate about the extent and type of emotional engagement a disinterested stance requires, for instance, whether fear during a horror movie can be disinterested.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] The aesthetic attitude is sometimes contrasted with other attitudes, such as the practical attitude, which is interested in usefulness and seeks to utilize or manipulate objects to achieve specific goals.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Similarly, it differs from the scientific attitude, which aims to explain phenomena and acquire factual knowledge about the world.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Some philosophers, such as Arthur Schopenhauer and Martin Heidegger, suggest that the aesthetic attitude can reveal aspects of reality obscured in other attitudes.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Aesthetic experience is further associated with aesthetic pleasure—a form of enjoyment in response to natural and artistic beauty.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] It is typically characterized as disinterested pleasure.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] It contrasts with interested pleasure that arises from the satisfaction of desires, such as the joy of achieving a personal goal or indulging in a particular type of food one craves.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Another difference is that aesthetic pleasure does not depend on the existence of the enjoyed object, like enjoying the beauty of a sunset in a dream.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] The joy in achieving a personal goal, by contrast, would be frustrated if one discovered that the achievement was merely a dream.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Philosophers like Immanuel Kant argue that aesthetic pleasure is preconceptual, meaning that it arises from a free interplay between imagination and understanding rather than from cognitive judgments or conceptual analysis.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] One view distinguishes refined from unrefined aesthetic pleasures based on whether the pleasure is evoked by a cultivated taste or an immediate, instinctual response.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Aesthetic pleasure is central to the characterization of many aesthetic phenomena that are said to involve or evoke such pleasure.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] However, the view that aesthetic pleasure is the defining characteristic of the entire aesthetic domain is controversial.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] It faces challenges in explaining phenomena such as the sublime, drama, tragedy, and forms of modern art, which may evoke diverse emotions not primarily linked to pleasure.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Aesthetic judgments are assessments of the aesthetic features and values of objects, expressed in statements like "this music is beautiful".
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] They can apply both to natural objects and artworks.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Aesthetic judgments also include assessments about how or why an object has aesthetic value without explicitly determining its overall aesthetic worth, as in the statement "this music is balanced".
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Many debates in aesthetics concern the nature of aesthetic judgments, in particular, whether they can be as objective and universal as empirical judgments made by natural scientists.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Subjectivists argue that aesthetic judgments express personal feelings and dislikes without universal validity.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] This view is contested by objectivists, who hold that aesthetic judgments describe objective features that are independent of the particular preferences of the judging individual.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Intermediate views suggest that the standards of aesthetic judgment are grounded in stable shared dispositions rather than variable individual preferences, resulting in a form of subjective universality.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] This position is reflected in Kant's view, which identifies four core features of aesthetic judgments: they are subjective, universal, disinterested, and involve an interplay of sense, imagination, and understanding.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Philosophers such as Francis Hutcheson and David Hume argue that there are general aesthetic principles or universal criteria that are applied when making aesthetic judgments.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Particularists, by contrast, assert that the unique nature of each aesthetic object requires a case-by-case evaluation that cannot be fully subsumed under general principles.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] A related debate between rationalism and the immediacy thesis concerns whether aesthetic judgments are mediated through concept application and reasoning or emerge directly from sensory intuition.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Aesthetic judgments rely on taste, which is a sensitivity to aesthetic qualities, a capacity to feel aesthetic pleasure, or an ability to discern beauty and other aesthetic qualities.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Taste is a type of preference expressed in immediate reactions and is sometimes understood as an inner sense or cognitive faculty.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Differences in taste are often used to explain why people disagree about aesthetic judgments and why the judgments of some people, such as art critics with extensive experience and a refined sense, carry more weight than those of casual observers.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Taste varies both among cultures and among individuals within a culture.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] There are also some cross-cultural agreements.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Several philosophers argue that taste can be learned to some extent and that the judgments of experienced observers follow similar standards, suggesting the existence of social norms of right and wrong aesthetic assessments.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] The term "aesthetic universal" refers to aspects of taste and other aesthetic phenomena that are shared across different cultures and societies, indicating common features of human nature underlying aesthetics.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Suggested general tendencies include the dispositions to engage in artistic expressions or to derive aesthetic pleasure from appreciating these expressions.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] The existence of more specific shared tendencies is debated.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] An example is the idea that humans generally find savanna-like landscapes with open grassy plains and scattered trees pleasing.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Art is a central topic of aesthetics and the main subject of the philosophy of art.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] It encompasses diverse forms, including painting, sculpture, music, dance, literature, and theater.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] This field covers both artworks and the skills or activities involved in their creation.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Artworks are artifacts or performances typically created by humans.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] They differ in this respect from naturally occurring aesthetic objects, like landscapes and sunsets.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] A central debate in the philosophy of art concerns the definition of art or how to distinguish it from non-art.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] There are many theories, each offering a unique perspective on the nature of art.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Essentialist approaches argue that there is an essence or a set of inherent features shared by all artworks and only by them.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] They often define artworks in terms of other aesthetic concepts, such as *representation*, *beauty*, or *aesthetic experience*.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] An early object-centered approach, first proposed by Plato, characterizes artworks as representations that seek to reflect or imitate certain aspects of reality.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Another definition suggests that artworks are objects designed to evoke aesthetic experiences or pleasure.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] A related approach proposes that all artworks have certain aesthetic properties in common, such as beauty.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Aesthetic formalism argues that specific formal features, such as a "significant form", are the hallmark of art.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Artist-centered approaches see artistic activity as the essential aspect of artworks.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] One conception understands artworks as special vehicles through which artists express emotions and other mental states.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Conventionalist definitions view art as a socially constructed category.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] This means that it does not primarily depend on the inherent properties of objects, for example, what they represent or what forms they have.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Instead, art is defined by social and cultural agreements, which are subject to change.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] A key motivation for this approach has been the emergence of modern art, which has challenged many earlier conceptions.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Conventionalist definitions can explain, for instance, that even mundane ready-made objects like a urinal are considered art if conventions say so.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Institutional theories argue that the conventions are set by social institutions of the art world.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Because of this social dependence, an object considered art in one society may not be art in another society.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Historical theories, another form of conventionalism, assert that the category of art depends on established traditions and historical contexts.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] They claim that an object becomes part of this category if it stands in the right relation to these traditions, for example, by being created in an artistic context and resembling other recognized artworks.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] There are also hybrid theories that combine elements from other theories.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] For instance, one approach holds that an object is an artwork if it either meets certain aesthetic standards or is conventionally regarded as art.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] The diversity of proposed definitions and the difficulties in reconciling them have led some philosophers to argue against the existence of precise criteria.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Some conclude that a definition is strictly impossible.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Others provide vague characterizations, suggesting that the domain of art is characterized by overlapping similarities, known as family resemblance.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] The ontology of art seeks to discern the fundamental categories of being to which all artworks belong.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] One approach argues that artworks are universals—general or repeatable entities that can have several instances at the same time.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] For example, a novel can have many copies, a film can have many screenings, and a photo can have many prints.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] One version of this view distinguishes artworks as types from their instances, which are considered tokens of this type.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] A different outlook rejects the idea that artworks are universals, arguing instead that they are particulars or unique concrete entities.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] For them, if there are several instances, then the artwork is the collection or sum of all instances.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] According to this view, Alfred Stieglitz's photograph *The Steerage* is not a type underlying its prints but rather the collection or sum of all prints together.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] A similar discussion addresses whether artworks are material objects, which exist independent of observers, or intentional objects, which exist in the experience of observers.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Pluralists argue that different types of artworks belong to distinct ontological categories.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Contextualists accept this view and further propose that the ontological category depends on the context of discussion.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Deflationism is skeptical about the fundamental existence of artworks in any form.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] It acknowledges that the term *art* may be practically useful in everyday language but rejects that it refers to any fundamental entities of reality.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Some distinctions focus on the medium used to express artistic ideas.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] For example, paintings typically use paint, such as oil or acrylic paint, which is distributed on a surface, whereas dance involves bodily movements.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Similarly, music is performed using instruments and voice to produce sounds, and literature relies on language.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Hybrid forms like opera and film combine several of these elements.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Another distinction is between performance works and object works.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Performance works, like a song performed on stage, are dynamically enacted in time, whereas object works, like a painting, have a more static nature.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Artworks can also be classified by art historic style, such as impressionism and surrealism, and by their intended purpose, like political and religious art.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] The meaning of an artwork is what is involved in understanding it or comprehending what it communicates, encompassing factors such as representation and expression.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Certain aspects of meaning may be directly accessible; others require in-depth interpretation, for example, to grasp symbolic or metaphorical elements.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Understanding influences aesthetic experience, and for certain artworks, a comprehensive understanding may be required to fully appreciate them.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] One approach to the analysis of meaning is the distinction between form and content.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Content refers to what is presented, such as the depicted topic, expressed ideas, and conceptual messages.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Form refers to how the content is presented, such as medium, technique, composition, and style.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Form encompasses modes of presentation in different art forms, like color and spatial arrangement in painting, harmony and rhythm in music, and narrative voice and plot structure in literature.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Representation is a depiction of real or imagined entities.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] For example, a portrait painting represents a person, and a fantasy novel represents an imaginary chain of events.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Similarity is a crucial element in many forms of artistic representation, meaning that the artwork resembles the depicted entity.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Representation can also happen through other means, such as conventional symbols and established codes.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] It is particularly prevalent in certain art forms and styles, such as classical art and realism.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Since antiquity, representation has been a key concept in theories of art, such as Plato's idea of defining art as imitation.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] However, it is controversial whether representation plays a central role in all art forms, including music and abstract modern art.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Expression is the conveyance of psychological states, such as emotions, moods, and attitudes.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] For example, a painter may depict a barren landscape in muted colors to express sadness, and a musician might use a fast tempo and upbeat melody to convey excitement.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] The expressed mental states often align with the artist's personal experience.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] However, this is not necessarily the case, and artists may explore psychological states they observed in others or entirely fictional experiences.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] An artwork can express a mental state like sadness by evoking it in the experience of the audience.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Alternatively, the expression can also happen if observers recognize the presence of sadness in the artwork even if they do not personally feel it.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Expression theories consider expression a core feature of artworks.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] They characterize artworks as expressions of the artist's mind, focusing on creativity and originality in the manifestation of aesthetic experiences.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] The process of interpretation is the attempt to uncover the meaning of an artwork to understand its significance and value.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] In the widest sense, interpretation encompasses any way of assigning meaning, including obvious descriptions of depicted entities and explanations of literal word meanings.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Interpretations aim to discover underlying aspects that are relevant to the understanding and appreciation of the artwork.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] The terms *interpretation* and *criticism* are sometimes used interchangeably.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] However, criticism is typically associated with more components, like a general description of the criticized artwork and a classification of style and genre.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Criticism also explains the art-historical background and evaluates positive and negative qualities.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Critics sometimes propose conflicting interpretations of the same artwork.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] According to critical monism, there is only one comprehensive correct interpretation, implying that conflicting interpretations cannot both be correct.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Critical pluralism, by contrast, asserts that there can be different but equally valid interpretations and that it is not always possible to determine which of two conflicting interpretations is superior.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] A similar debate addresses whether interpretations can be true or false in an objective sense.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Several frameworks of interpretation have been proposed.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] According to intentionalism, the meaning of an artwork is determined by the author's intent—their reasons and motives that led to the creation of the artwork.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] This typically involves analyzing the ideas the artist aimed to express but can also include a biographical analysis to learn about psychological and social circumstances in the artist's life.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Intentionalism is a controversial theory, termed the *intentional fallacy* by its critics.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Some objections point to cases where the author's intention cannot be known, where the author cannot be identified, or where no traditional author exists, as in artworks created by artificial intelligence.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] In these cases, meaning would be inaccessible or non-existent.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Other objections assert that an artist may fail to accurately express their intention or may manifest unintended aesthetic features, suggesting that an artwork can contain both less and more than the artist intended.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] An alternative to intentionalism argues that meaning is determined by artistic, stylistic, linguistic, and other cultural conventions.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] For example, linguistic conventions determine the literal meanings of words and thereby influence the overall meaning of a poem.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Another framework holds that meaning is shaped by how the audience, rather than the author, interprets or would interpret the intention underlying the work.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Artistic formalism proposes a different approach by focusing interpretation exclusively on formal or perceptual features of artworks.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Aestheticism and instrumentalism are theories about the value of art.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Aestheticism asserts that the primary value of art lies in its intrinsic aesthetic merits, independent of any external purposes.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] This idea of the autonomy of art is expressed in the slogan "art for art's sake".
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Strong forms of aestheticism not only disregard external purposes but see them as detrimental influences that undermine artistic integrity.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Instrumentalism, by contrast, explains the value of art by the effects it has on other domains.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] It understands art as a means to things such as moral education, spiritual growth, therapeutic benefits, and social cohesion.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] The individual arts are practices or disciplines in the domain of art.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] They encompass a wide range of fields, including traditionally established forms such as painting, music, and literature, as well as newer types like video games.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] One classification divides them into visual arts, literary arts, and performance arts.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] The boundaries between these categories are not always clear, and alternative classifications have been proposed.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Painting is a visual art in which a painter applies colors to a surface.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] It allows for a diverse range of motives and styles, and is often considered a paradigm form of art.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] The representation of real entities plays a central role in many forms of painting, ranging from landscapes and people to historic events.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] This process involves artistic choices that go beyond simple replication, such as guiding the viewer's attention to specific aspects or highlighting important but easily overlooked features.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] The issue of representation is also crucial in photography, a visual art shaped by technological developments in camera design and editing processes.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] A key topic in the philosophy of photography concerns its mechanical manner of authentically representing real objects, frequently drawing parallels and distinctions with painting.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] The status of photographs as true artworks is disputed, with critics arguing that the mechanical nature of capturing images lacks the necessary artistic creativity.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Music is a performance art in which sounds are combined to create aesthetic patterns, relying on aspects such as melody and rhythm.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Unlike painting and photography, it is typically less associated with objective representation and more closely linked to the expression of emotions.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] A key discussion in the philosophy of music concerns the definition of music or the criteria under which a combination of sounds qualifies as music.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Proposals range from objective criteria, such as the patterns of how sounds are organized, to subjective criteria, focusing on audience experience and interpretation.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Dance is another performance art in which dancers create aesthetic patterns through a series of bodily movements, often following a choreography.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] It is typically accompanied by music and shares with music an emphasis on expressive features.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Architecture is the art or craft of designing and building, encompassing a wide range of structures from monuments and cathedrals to skyscrapers and residential homes.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] It typically combines aesthetic with functional goals, seeking to create buildings that are both visually appealing and practically useful.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] This dual nature is a central topic of the philosophy of architecture, with one theory suggesting that mere buildings can be distinguished from artistic architecture by the presence of decorative elements.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Sculpture is another art form that, like architecture, involves the creation of three-dimensional works.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Sculptures are usually static objects made of robust materials like stone, metal, and wood, but may also include dynamic elements, as is the case for kinetic sculptures.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Key discussions in the philosophy of sculpture address the definition, representational aspects, and aesthetic features of sculptures as well as the influence of the chosen material.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Literature has language as its primary medium.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] In its widest sense, literature encompasses any written document.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] However, the term is typically used in a narrower sense in aesthetics for forms of writing that belong to the high arts, such as poems, novels, and drama.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Literature as an art is often characterized by its deliberate, elaborate, and organized use of language, but there is no universally accepted demarcation between artistic literature and other forms of writing.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Poetry is a distinct form of literature often written in verses composed of several lines that may follow specific patterns, such as meter and rhyme.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Many poems are characterized by an economical use of language that seeks to evoke specific experiences while being difficult to paraphrase.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Theater is a performance art that combines elements from other art forms.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] It typically includes a carefully prepared set or stage where actors perform, usually incorporating storytelling and sound design to create immersive experiences.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Theater is performed before a live audience, which can create a sense of immediacy that is less prevalent in related art forms, such as film.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Film also integrates aspects from several artistic disciplines but relies more heavily on technological means of recording and editing.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Films can involve actors but may also include animated characters or document real-life events.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] They are normally the result of collaborative efforts of many people, which complicates the identification of a singular author in the traditional sense.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Video games are a more recent form of art.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Like theater and film, they usually blend visual, auditory, and narrative elements.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] They typically stand out through their emphasis on player interaction, allowing active exploration of and engagement with the game world.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] The status of films and video games as serious forms of art is disputed.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] Proponents tend to emphasize their aesthetic qualities; critics often point to their association with mass production and popular culture as counterarguments.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p01] For video games, a related debate centers on the elements of competition and winning, questioning whether these elements run counter to the spirit of art.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] Aesthetic phenomena are investigated in several fields.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] Some areas examine the relationship between aesthetics and other branches of philosophy or compare different artistic traditions; others study aesthetic elements in everyday life or engage in scientific inquiry using empirical methods.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] Ethics is the branch of philosophy that studies moral phenomena in general and right behavior in particular.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] Artworks can have ethical consequences by influencing how people feel, perceive, and evaluate their circumstances.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] For example, artworks can glorify violence and reinforce biases, just as they can inspire empathy and challenge societal norms.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] As a result, art is also relevant to the field of politics since it can steer political sentiment to legitimize authority or mobilize resistance, thereby influencing voter attitudes.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] Artworks can also explore morally relevant topics without expressing a clear positive or negative evaluation, such as a novel examining an ethical dilemma without favoring one solution over the others.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] Since both ethics and aesthetics deal with values, philosophers seek to clarify the relationship between moral and aesthetic values, proposing several theories of their interaction.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] Ethicism asserts that the moral value of an artwork can increase its aesthetic value, while ethical defects may undermine its artistic merit.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] This view is reversed by immoralism, which suggests that in some cases, moral flaws enhance aesthetic experience.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] Autonomism rejects both positions, arguing that these domains of evaluation are independent.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] Scientific approaches rooted in psychology and related fields employ empirical methods to conduct inquiries and justify hypotheses.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] The psychology of aesthetics examines the mental processes involved in the perception and appreciation of beauty and art, using methods such as experimentation, observation, and surveys.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] Experimental aesthetics is an early and influential approach pioneered by Gustav Fechner.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] It follows a bottom-up methodology that starts with human sensation, investigating preferences to simple physical stimuli, such as basic colors and shapes.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] Gestalt psychology relies on a more holistic outlook, examining how composition and object placement influence aesthetic experience, like the relationship between balanced organization and a sense of calm.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] Some works, such as Daniel Berlyne's approach, shift the focus from perception to emotion, suggesting that features like novelty and complexity cause arousal and that the right amount of arousal is pleasurable.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] Psychological analysis also examines the temporal structure of aesthetic experiences of art.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] One outlook identifies two phases: an initial impression in which the observer forms a rough general idea of the artwork's topic, structure, and meaning, followed by a focal analysis of more specific features.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] Research further explores how circumstances influence aesthetic experience, like the contrast between encountering a painting in a museum or a shopping mall.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] Along with physical circumstances, social and personal factors also influence aesthetic experience, such as group dynamics, prior knowledge, and the motivation for seeking the experience.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] Evolutionary psychology analyzes mental phenomena as products of natural selection.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] It asserts that genetic variations responsible for new capacities are passed on to future generations if they enhance survival and reproduction.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] Adopting this approach, evolutionary aesthetics interprets beauty and other aesthetic experiences as adaptive traits that guide fitness-relevant preferences.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] Examples are aesthetic preferences for environments conducive to survival, such as landscapes resembling the African savanna, and sexual selection by identifying genetically fit mates.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] By focusing on the relatively permanent biological nature of humans, evolutionary psychology sees aesthetic values as universal or transcultural patterns of taste and appreciation, contrasting with subjectivist theories that understand aesthetic values as cultural constructs.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] Neuroaesthetics applies neuroscientific insights and methods to study the relationship between brain activity and aesthetic experience.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] Aesthetic experiences arise from brain processes responsible for organizing sensory stimuli, forming cognitive interpretations, and generating emotional responses.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] Neuroaesthetics examines these processes using empirical methods, including neuroimaging techniques like fMRI.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] In one type of experiment, participants view artworks, some considered beautiful and others ugly, with researchers noting that the brain area known as the orbitofrontal cortex is more active when viewing beautiful paintings.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] Cognitive science, another field, employs an interdisciplinary approach to study mental phenomena by examining how they access and transform information.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] An influential theory, suggested by Ernst Gombrich, analyzes aesthetic experience through the interplay of low-level and high-level information processes: sensory processes provide low-level information, which is organized and interpreted using high-level conceptual background knowledge.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] Another approach analyzes aesthetic representation through the modularity of mind—the hypothesis that the mind is composed of mental modules that function independently.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] It argues that paintings represent real objects by triggering the same mental modules responsible for the recognition of those objects.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] Comparative aesthetics examines diverse aesthetic traditions, analyzing the similarities and differences in their standards of beauty and theoretical approaches.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] For example, the focus in Western aesthetics on high art and its separation from everyday affairs is not common in most other traditions, for which art is typically closely integrated with practical functions in everyday life, including religion and moral education.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] Artistic differences between different traditions also encompass dominant media, common styles, and chosen motifs.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] The comparison of cultural products from different traditions presents conceptual challenges associated with tradition-specific aesthetic concepts and standards of evaluation.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] The uncritical application of standards from one tradition to evaluate the works of another can result in cultural imperialism.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] At the same time, these differences provide opportunities to artists and philosophers to incorporate new elements and explore novel perspectives.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] Indian aesthetics draws a close connection between artistic activity and religious practice.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] It argues that artistic expression is a spiritual endeavor that should be informed by knowledge of the self and reality, express devotion to the divine, and avoid attachments to the fruits of the activity.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] Traditional Indian aesthetics analyzes art in terms of basic life emotions, called rasas, such as delight, humor, sadness, and anger.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] It sees art as a play that imitates reality by conveying experiences of the rasas.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] Its focus is on the universal expressions of human emotional life rather than person-specific feelings.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] This school of thought identifies artistic creativity as the ability to harness the full potential of the medium, like colors, sounds, and words, to convey experiential universals.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] For the audience, it recommends an aesthetic attitude characterized by a psychic distance from private concerns to transcend the personal self and become receptive to universal elements.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] Chinese aesthetics emphasizes the spontaneous nature of artistic creativity and its connection to the moral and spiritual domains.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] It argues that art should foster harmony within society and align with the natural order of the universe.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] In this role, art is both self-expression and self-cultivation aimed at promoting social well-being.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] The main focus of Chinese aesthetics is on poetry, painting, and calligraphy, known as the three perfections.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] This tradition influenced Japanese aesthetics, which is characterized by its interest in nature.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] Different art styles in this tradition are shaped by religious outlooks, particularly Shinto and Buddhism.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] Japanese theories of art stress the interrelation between the experience of the artist and the response of the audience.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] Islamic philosophers see art as a means of communicating philosophical and religious truths, making them accessible to the general public without requiring abstract theoretical thought.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] Thinkers such as Al-Farabi and Avicenna argued that imagination rather than reasoning underlies artistic creation and appreciation.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] According to this view, art imitates reality and evokes emotions to convey underlying truths and positively influence behavior.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] Religious teachings play a central role in Islamic aesthetics.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] For example, the belief that Allah is transcendent and boundless has resulted in the avoidance of figurative depictions and the emphasis on abstract art forms.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] African aesthetics emphasizes the intuitive and emotional nature of art, highlighting its communal function in social life.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] Early scholarship on this tradition was typically conducted from an ethnocentric perspective using Western aesthetic standards to interpret and evaluate African art.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] This usually resulted in the portrayal of African artworks as exotic curiosities that lack the sophistication of high art.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] The emergence of indigenous scholarship in the 20th century sought to correct this interpretation, arguing that the emphasis on moral, emotional, and intuitive aspects reflects different artistic standards rather than a deficiency.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] This school of thought, often associated with the concept of Négritude, focuses on the importance of feelings in contrast to abstraction and intellectual analysis.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] Environmental aesthetics deals with the appreciation of nature, including elements such as forests, mountain ranges, rivers, and flowers.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] It encompasses both transient appearances, such as the fleeting beauty of a landscape during sunset, and enduring aspects, such as the majesty of a centuries-old tree.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] This field focuses on sensory and formal qualities associated with beauty and related aesthetic qualities.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] In this respect, it contrasts with the philosophy of art, which typically emphasizes the interpretation of underlying meanings associated with expression and representation.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] Some approaches to environmental aesthetics also consider the impact of background knowledge on the aesthetic experience of nature.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] For instance, ecological awareness of the intricate relationships within an ecosystem can shape the appreciation of a woodland environment by understanding it as a habitat of diverse species.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] In its broadest sense, environmental aesthetics encompasses the appreciation of any environment, including those created by humans.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] This inquiry is closely associated with everyday aesthetics, which examines aesthetic phenomena encountered in daily life.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] Everyday aesthetics covers both public and private environments, ranging from modern cities and industrial sites to private homes and backyards, as well as personal adornments and consumer products, such as clothing, hairstyles, industrial design, and web design.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] The aesthetics of popular art, a related discipline, investigates aesthetic qualities in popular culture and compares the evaluative standards of popular art with those of high or fine art.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] For example, it studies the contrast between commercial mass art and experimental avant-garde and explores specific types of popular art, such as kitsch.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] Art plays a central role in the field of religion and manifests in many forms, including paintings, sculptures, architecture, music, dance, and literature.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] Its key characteristic comes from its religious function, such as conveying theological and moral teachings, representing symbolic truths, inspiring religious experiences, and aiding devotional practices.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] Religious art is part of all major religions and was the dominant art form during ancient and medieval times.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] Its influence began to wane in the modern period due to secularization.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] This shift is also reflected in developments in the philosophy of art that introduced a focus on disinterestedness and the autonomy of aesthetic experience from external purposes, including religious goals.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] Several theories of aesthetics are associated with specific philosophical schools of thought.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] Marxist aesthetics examines the relationship between art, class structure, and social ideology, exploring how art can enforce or challenge established power hierarchies.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] Feminist aesthetics criticizes male biases in aesthetic theory and artistic practice while discussing alternatives.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] It investigates unfair social institutions and aesthetic standards that disadvantage women and exclude them from the art world.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] An example is the male gaze—a cultural phenomenon that treats women as objects of male spectatorship rather than as artistic creators.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] Postmodern aesthetics is a diverse movement that challenges established concepts and theories in the field of aesthetics.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] It typically rejects the focus on disinterested pleasure, the autonomy of art from other domains, and the distinction between high and popular art.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] It tends to promote a pluralism that embraces diversity, playfulness, and irony.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] The term mathematical beauty refers to aesthetic qualities of abstract mathematical concepts and theories.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] For instance, a mathematical proof may be considered beautiful if it demonstrates a profound insight in an effective manner or reveals an underlying unity of seemingly disparate mathematical ideas.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] The aesthetics of science examines aesthetic judgments about scientific theories and practices, including the role of beauty and creativity in the construction of models.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] Computer art involves the use of computers in the creation of artworks.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] It can take many forms, ranging from minor digital enhancements of existing artworks to entirely new creations generated using complex algorithms.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] Its abstract nature, based on symbolic representation and manipulation of electronic signals, distinguishes computer art from traditional forms of art, which rely on more tangible media.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] This medium offers new artistic possibilities, such as virtual reality and interactivity.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] Rapid developments in artificial intelligence in the 21st century have significantly impacted computer art.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] They include the emergence of generative models—systems that are trained using existing media to create new texts, images, music, or videos in response to verbal descriptions of the intended result.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] Examples include ChatGPT, Stable Diffusion, MuseNet, and RunwayML.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] Meta-aesthetics examines the fundamental assumptions and concepts underlying aesthetics.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] It asks about the existence of aesthetic facts, the meaning of aesthetic statements, and the ways of acquiring aesthetic knowledge.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] A central meta-aesthetic debate between realism and anti-realism addresses whether there are mind-independent aesthetic facts.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] A related discussion between cognitivism and non-cognitivism considers whether aesthetic statements can be objectively true or primarily express personal emotions.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] Aesthetics has its roots in ancient thought, which typically interpreted beauty as a metaphysical phenomenon associated with the order of the cosmos.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] In ancient Greek philosophy, early explorations of the nature of beauty are found in Pythagorean philosophy in the 5th and 4th centuries BCE.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] This tradition proposed that beauty arises from the proportion and harmony between different elements.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] In works like the *Philebus* and *Symposium*, Plato (427–347 BCE) analyzed pure beauty as an immutable form that exists independently of matter.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] He argued that material entities are beautiful if they participate in the form of beauty.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] Plato understood art as a craft that seeks to imitate and represent material entities.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] He acknowledged that art has some didactic value but was overall critical of it, asserting that its derivative nature, based on imitation of sensible features, cannot lead to true knowledge.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] Aristotle (384–322 BCE) examined aesthetics through the lens of poetry, providing a detailed analysis in his book *Poetics*.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] He agreed with Plato's idea that art is a form of imitation but adopted a more positive outlook, proposing that it can reveal universal truths.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] Aristotle suggested that successful artistic imitation is pleasurable and can have therapeutic or cathartic effects.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] By linking this pleasure to beauty, he tried to explain why the imitation of unpleasurable phenomena, like tragic stories, can be enjoyable.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] Also influenced by Plato, Plotinus (204–270 CE) argued that beauty is not based on sensory symmetries or simple proportions but embodies an underlying order, harmony, and unity associated with the ultimate source of creation.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] In ancient India, the Natya Shastra, traditionally attributed to Bharata (c.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] 200 CE), formulated the rasa theory of art.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] This theory posits that the goal of art is to convey fundamental life emotions as experiential universals of human existence.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] In ancient China, the philosophy of art was shaped by Confucianism.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] It emphasized self-cultivation and the relation between nature and human culture.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] During the medieval period, the rise of Christianity led Western aesthetic thinkers to blend ancient Greek thought with religious teachings, often in the form of philosophical theology.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] Influenced by Plato and Plotinus, Augustine of Hippo (354–430 CE) explored the distinction between artistic creation, which transforms matter, and divine creation, which brings forth existence out of nothing.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] He thought that all beauty originates from God and analyzed it in terms of unity, equality, number, proportion, and order.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] Thomas Aquinas defined beauty as what brings pleasure upon perception.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] For him, the mind plays a central role in this process since beauty lies in the immaterial form of the perceived object that the mind recognizes in the sensory data.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] Aquinas saw beauty as a basic category of being and identified it with proportion, radiance, and integrity.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] An integration of Greek philosophy and religious thought also happened in the Islamic world.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] 950 CE) associated beauty with pleasure and understood it as a degree of perfection and a divine attribute of Allah.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] 980 – 1037 CE) distinguished sensible from intelligible beauty and explored psychological processes underlying aesthetic judgments, such as the role of imagination.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] Meanwhile, in India, the rasa theory of art expanded to also encompass devotional practices, including efforts to portray or evoke profound religious experiences of the union with the divine.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] 1025 CE) elaborated the spiritual dimension of the rasa theory, drawing a sharp distinction between ordinary worldly emotions and rasas as transcendent aesthetic emotions.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] 5th to 6th centuries CE) combined Daoist and Confucian ideas, suggesting that artists align with the natural order of the universe and spontaneously express the movement of life in their artworks.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] He also proposed a set of basic principles of painting.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] 1090 CE) argued that artworks reflect the moral character and spiritual outlook of the artist, which he saw as a central factor of the artwork's aesthetic value.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] During this period, the growing influence of Buddhism on Chinese aesthetic thought led to an artistic shift from objective reality to subjective experiences as a result of Buddhist teachings on the illusory nature of reality.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] The medieval period in the West came to an end with the emergence of the Renaissance starting in the 15th century.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] This change led to the revival of classical aesthetic ideals while secularization paved the way for rationalist inquiries into general laws of beauty and empiricist analyses of sensory and emotional experiences in the subsequent Age of Enlightenment.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] Modern aesthetics emerged in the 18th century, as philosophers engaged more systematically with the subject.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] A key step in this process happened through the philosophy of Alexander Baumgarten (1714–1762), who first conceived aesthetics as a distinct field of inquiry: the science of sensory cognitions or the study of what is sensed and imagined.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] In British philosophy, Francis Hutcheson (1694–1746) followed ideas of the third Earl of Shaftesbury (1671–1713) and provided an early theory of taste, conceptualizing it as an internal sense responsible for aesthetic apprehension.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] This outlook inspired David Hume (1711–1776) to develop a subjective theory of beauty, understanding it as a pleasurable sentiment caused by perceptions.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] He combined this perspective with the idea that beauty follows intersubjective standards as shared principles of taste governing which objects are experienced as beautiful.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] Immanuel Kant (1724–1804) expanded Hume's idea that aesthetic judgments are both subjective and universal, arguing that the underlying pleasure must be disinterested to follow universal standards.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] According to Kant, this type of pleasure comes from a free play in which the mental faculties of imagination and understanding harmoniously interact.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] In response to earlier theories by Edmund Burke (1729–1797), Kant also examined the sublime as a distinct aesthetic quality.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] Kant's thought inspired diverse developments in German philosophy.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] Friedrich Schiller (1759–1805) saw art as a unifying phenomenon that synthesizes different basic human drives in a type of play.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] J. von Schelling (1775–1854) shared a similar perspective, arguing that art reconciles opposites and reveals the underlying unity of the self and nature.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] Hegel (1770–1831) studied aesthetics through his philosophical system of absolute idealism, seeing artistic beauty as the sensory manifestation of truth.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] Combining Kantian and Indian philosophy, Arthur Schopenhauer (1788–1860) understood disinterested aesthetic experience as a suspension of the will, resulting in a temporary peace of mind by interrupting the cycle of striving and suffering.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] He inspired the Chinese philosopher Wang Guowei (1877–1927), who integrated Schopenhauer's ideas with Buddhist thought.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] Wang viewed the goal of art as the creation of worlds within the world, which are open to disinterested reflection.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] Friedrich Nietzsche (1844–1900) rejected the disinterestedness of aesthetic experience and the autonomy of art from other domains.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] Instead, he considered art an expression of the struggle between opposing life forces, seeing it as a vehicle of transformation and life affirmation.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] Following the thought of Karl Marx (1818–1883), Marxist aesthetic philosophers like Leon Trotsky (1879–1940) and Georg Lukács (1885–1971) examined how art reflects and shapes social ideologies and power hierarchies.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] Drawing from Marxist ideas, Theodor Adorno (1903–1969) critiqued the commodification of art and explored its ability to express alienation and challenge societal norms.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] Also adopting a Marxist perspective, Walter Benjamin (1892–1940) studied how advances in technological reproducibility transform art.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] Romanticist thought emphasized artistic originality, creativity, and the expression of profound feelings, as formulated in the works of J.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] It saw artworks as products of human genius that defy rule-based understanding.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] This school of thought inspired the theory of expressionism, which asserts that the primary function of art is to communicate emotions and other mental states.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] It was examined by thinkers such as Leo Tolstoy (1828–1910), Benedetto Croce (1866–1952), and R.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] Intentionalism, a closely related position, focuses on the author's intent as the source of meaning of artworks.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] Monroe Beardsley (1915–1985) opposed this view, arguing that meaning is not fixed by private intentions.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] Sigmund Freud (1856–1939) and Carl Jung (1875–1961) interpreted art through a psychoanalytic perspective as expressions of the unconscious, an approach also later explored by Richard Wollheim (1923–2005).
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] In the late 19th and early 20th centuries, aestheticism became a prominent view in English-speaking philosophy.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] For example, Walter Pater (1839–1894) and Oscar Wilde (1854–1900) proposed that art is an end in itself without an ulterior purpose.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] Pragmatists rejected this outlook and the idea that aesthetic experience is disinterested.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] For instance, John Dewey (1859–1952) proposed in his 1934 book *Art as Experience* that the value of art lies in the unique experiences it provides, which can lead to individual and societal improvements.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] Formalism became another influential theory of art in the early 20th century.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] It dismisses the focus on expressive and representational aspects and argues instead that artworks are defined by formal features, like the arrangement of perceptual qualities.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] Clive Bell (1881–1964), a major proponent of this view, termed this arrangement "significant form".
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] The emergence of Dadaism and conceptual art challenged traditional definitions of art based on intrinsic features of artworks.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] Danto (1924–2013) and George Dickie (1926–2020) to propose institutional definitions, arguing that social conventions set by the art world determine which objects are artworks.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] Mary Mothersill (1923–2008) challenged these developments.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] She aimed to restore earlier conceptions of beauty associated with Aquinas, Hume, and Kant, focusing on the apprehension of aesthetic qualities.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] In continental philosophy, the school of phenomenology studied the immediate experience of art.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] For example, it examined how artworks can depict unreal objects, how imagination is involved in the process, and how art can reveal features of reality.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] This tradition is closely related to existentialist aesthetics, which views artworks as expressions of human freedom that can authentically portray central aspects of the human condition.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] The philosophy of Martin Heidegger (1889–1976) influenced both traditions.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] He criticized the focus on disinterested pleasure found in modern philosophy of art, arguing that artworks can reveal truths about human existence and provide new perspectives of understanding.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] Heidegger's student Hans-Georg Gadamer (1900–2002) further investigated the relation between art and truth, examining aesthetic experience and traditional theories through phenomenological analysis and hermeneutic interpretation.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] Postmodern thinkers, like Roland Barthes (1915–1980) and Jacques Derrida (1930–2004), challenged the separation of art from everyday life and the idea that artworks have a stable meaning or universal value.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] They suggested instead that artistic merit depends on historical and cultural contexts.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] Starting in the 1970s, feminist perspectives challenged male-centric theories and practices within aesthetic philosophy and the art world.
[src:false-color/aesthetics-p02] For example, Simone de Beauvoir (1908–1986) and Luce Irigaray (born 1930) explored how feminine perspectives are marginalized by masculine standards.
[src:false-color/afterimage] An **afterimage**, or **after-image**, is an image that continues to appear in the eyes after a period of exposure to the original image.
[src:false-color/afterimage] An afterimage may be a normal phenomenon (physiological afterimage) or may be pathological (palinopsia).
[src:false-color/afterimage] Illusory palinopsia may be a pathological exaggeration of physiological afterimages.
[src:false-color/afterimage] Afterimages occur because photochemical activity in the retina continues even when the eyes are no longer experiencing the original stimulus.
[src:false-color/afterimage] The remainder of this article refers to **physiological afterimages**.
[src:false-color/afterimage] A common physiological afterimage is the dim area that seems to float before one's eyes after briefly looking into a light source, such as a camera flash.
[src:false-color/afterimage] Palinopsia is a common symptom of visual snow.
[src:false-color/afterimage] Negative afterimages are generated in the retina but may be modified like other retinal signals by neural adaptation of the retinal ganglion cells that carry signals from the retina of the eye to the rest of the brain.
[src:false-color/afterimage] Normally, any image is moved over the retina by small eye movements known as microsaccades before much adaptation can occur.
[src:false-color/afterimage] However, if the image is very intense and brief, or if the image is large, or if the eye remains very steady, these small movements cannot keep the image on unadapted parts of the retina.
[src:false-color/afterimage] Afterimages can be seen when moving from a bright environment to a dim one, like walking indoors on a bright snowy day.
[src:false-color/afterimage] They are accompanied by neural adaptation in the occipital lobe of the brain that function similar to color balance adjustments in photography.
[src:false-color/afterimage] These adaptations attempt to keep vision consistent in dynamic lighting.
[src:false-color/afterimage] Viewing a uniform background while adaptation is still occurring will allow an individual to see the afterimage because localized areas of vision are still being processed by the brain using adaptations that are no longer needed.
[src:false-color/afterimage] The Young-Helmholtz trichromatic theory of color vision postulated that there were three types of photoreceptors in the eye, each sensitive to a particular range of visible light: short-wavelength cones, medium-wavelength cones, and long-wavelength cones.
[src:false-color/afterimage] Trichromatic theory, however, cannot explain all afterimage phenomena.
[src:false-color/afterimage] Specifically, afterimages are the complementary hue of the adapting stimulus, and trichromatic theory fails to account for this fact.
[src:false-color/afterimage] The failure of trichromatic theory to account for afterimages indicates the need for an opponent-process theory such as that articulated by Ewald Hering (1878) and further developed by Hurvich and Jameson (1957).
[src:false-color/afterimage] The opponent process theory states that the human visual system interprets color information by processing signals from cones and rods in an antagonistic manner.
[src:false-color/afterimage] The opponent color theory is that there are four opponent channels: red versus cyan, green vs magenta, blue versus yellow, and black versus white.
[src:false-color/afterimage] Responses to one color of an opponent channel are antagonistic to those of the other color.
[src:false-color/afterimage] Therefore, a green image will produce a magenta afterimage.
[src:false-color/afterimage] The green color adapts the green channel, so they produce a weaker signal.
[src:false-color/afterimage] Anything resulting in less green is interpreted as its paired primary color, which is magenta (an equal mixture of red and blue).
[src:false-color/afterimage] Positive afterimages, by contrast, appear the same color as the original image.
[src:false-color/afterimage] They are often very brief, lasting less than half a second.
[src:false-color/afterimage] The cause of positive afterimages is not well known, but possibly reflects persisting activity in the brain when the retinal photoreceptor cells continue to send neural impulses to the occipital lobe.
[src:false-color/afterimage] A stimulus which elicits a positive image will usually trigger a negative afterimage quickly via the adaptation process.
[src:false-color/afterimage] To experience this phenomenon, one can look at a bright source of light and then look away to a dark area, such as by closing the eyes.
[src:false-color/afterimage] At first one should see a fading positive afterimage, likely followed by a negative afterimage that may last for much longer.
[src:false-color/afterimage] It is also possible to see afterimages of random objects that are not bright, only these last for a split second and go unnoticed by most people.
[src:false-color/afterimage] An afterimage in general is an optical illusion that refers to an image continuing to appear after exposure to the original image has ceased.
[src:false-color/afterimage] Prolonged viewing of the colored patch induces an afterimage of the complementary color (for example, yellow color induces a bluish afterimage).
[src:false-color/afterimage] The "afterimage on empty shape" effect is related to a class of effects referred to as contrast effects.
[src:false-color/afterimage] In this effect, an empty (white) shape is presented on a colored background for several seconds.
[src:false-color/afterimage] When the background color disappears (becomes white), an illusionary color similar to the original background is perceived within the shape.
[src:false-color/analogous-colors] In color theory, **analogous** colors are groups of colors that are next to each other on the color wheel.
[src:false-color/analogous-colors] Red, orange, and red-orange are examples.
[src:false-color/analogous-colors] The term *analogous* refers to having analogy, or corresponding to something in particular.
[src:false-color/analogous-colors] This color scheme strength comes to the fact that it lacks contrast as in comparison to its counterpart, the complementary schemes.
[src:false-color/analogous-colors] These color schemes are most often seen in nature.
[src:false-color/analogous-colors] For example, during the fall, one might often see the changing leaves form an analogous sort of color scheme, progressively moving through the color wheel to create a gradient in its natural pattern.
[src:false-color/analogous-colors] High-key color schemes have a lighter value, having white added to them or water in the case of watercolors.
[src:false-color/analogous-colors] These have a more pastel-like look to them.
[src:false-color/analogous-colors] Having a high-key analogous color scheme can give a piece a stimulating shimmer that pleases the eye, making everything seem the same color at first until approach.
[src:false-color/analogous-colors] The colors are pure and are not affected by their complements which grab attention.
[src:false-color/analogous-colors] This was commonly used in impressionism by artists such as Monet, Pissarro, and Degas.
[src:false-color/analogous-colors] Pierre Bonnard has also been noted for using it.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] Born to working-class Rusyn immigrant parents in Pittsburgh, Warhol began his career as a commercial artist in New York before transitioning to fine art.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] Among his best-known early silkscreen paintings are *Campbell's Soup Can* (1962), *Marilyn Diptych* (1962), and *Coca-Cola (3)* (1962).
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] In the mid-1960s, Warhol began devoting his attention to creating experimental films such as *Blow Job* (1964) and *Empire* (1965).
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] He subsequently directed a number of underground films—including *Chelsea Girls* (1966), *Four Stars* (1967), and *Blue Movie* (1969)—featuring a shifting group of personalities known as Warhol superstars.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] His studio, the Factory, became a hub for avant-garde experimentation, bringing together drag queens, poets, bohemians, musicians, and wealthy patrons.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] Warhol also managed the influential rock band the Velvet Underground, who performed at his Exploding Plastic Inevitable (1966–67) multimedia events.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] After Warhol survived an assassination attempt in 1968, the Factory evolved into a business enterprise.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] He founded *Interview* magazine, produced the play *Pork* (1971), and published various books such as *The Philosophy of Andy Warhol* (1975) and *Popism* (1980).
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] He executed several series of paintings—notably *Mao* (1972–73), *Athletes* (1977), and *Last Supper* (1985–86)—and commissioned portraiture, while expanding into television with *Andy Warhol's TV* (1980–83) and *Andy Warhol's Fifteen Minutes* (1985–87).
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] He meticulously documented his social life through photography and daily recordings, published posthumously as *The Andy Warhol Diaries* (1989).
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] Warhol died of cardiac arrhythmia at the age of 58 following gallbladder surgery in 1987.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] Warhol has been described as the "bellwether of the art market", with several of his works ranking among the most expensive paintings ever sold.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] In 2013, *Silver Car Crash (Double Disaster)* (1963) sold for $105 million.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] In 2022, *Shot Sage Blue Marilyn* (1964) sold for $195 million, the highest price ever paid at auction for a work by an American artist.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] Warhol has been the subject of numerous retrospective exhibitions, books, and documentary films.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] The Andy Warhol Museum in Pittsburgh, which holds an extensive permanent collection of his art and archives, is the largest in the United States dedicated to a single artist.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] Warhol was born on August 6, 1928, in Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] He was the fourth child of Andrej Varchola (Americanized as Andrew Warhola; c.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] His parents were working-class Rusyn emigrants from Mikó, Austria-Hungary (now Miková in northeast Slovakia).
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] In 1912, Warhol's father emigrated to the United States and found work in a coal mine.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] His wife joined him nine years later in 1921.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] The family lived at 55 Beelen Street and later at 3252 Dawson Street in the Oakland neighborhood of Pittsburgh.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] They were Ruthenian Catholic and attended St.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] John Chrysostom Byzantine Catholic Church.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] Warhol had two older brothers, Paul (1922–2014) and John (1925–2010), as well as an older sister, Maria (1912; died in infancy).
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] Warhol's nephew James Warhola, became a successful children's book illustrator.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] At the age of eight, Warhol had a streptococcal infection that led to scarlet fever.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] Because there were no antibiotics to treat the illness, it progressed to rheumatic fever and ultimately the neurological condition Sydenham's chorea, sometimes referred to as St.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] At times he was confined to bed and made to remain home from school.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] He would spend these days drawing, creating scrapbooks from Hollywood magazines, and cutting out images from comic books that his mother bought him.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] He also enjoyed using the family's Kodak Baby Brownie Special camera, and after noticing his passion for photography, his father and brothers built a darkroom in the basement for him.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] When Warhol started art classes at Holmes School in 1937, his teacher recognized his talent and arranged for him to attend Saturday drawing classes at the Carnegie Institute in Pittsburgh.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] In May 1942, as Warhol was preparing to graduate from Holmes School, his father died of tubercular peritonitis, after having years earlier drunk contaminated water from a coal mine in West Virginia.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] Warhol attended Schenley High School in Pittsburgh, where he excelled academically and artistically.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] His tenth-grade art teacher, Mary Adeline McKibbin encouraged him to enter a national Scholastic Corporation's art contest, which she also helped organize locally.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] The competition drew high school entries from across the United States, with tens of thousands of works submitted and regional selections exhibited at the Carnegie Museum of Art.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] McKibbin later claimed Warhol won a Scholastic award.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] However, biographer Blake Gopnik notes that contemporary coverage of the 1944 and 1945 contests suggests he did not receive a major prize, scholarship, or War Bond award.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] At most, Warhol appears to have earned an unpublicized "honorable mention," the gold pin for which he reportedly still wore in the 1980s.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] After graduating from Schenley High School in 1945, Warhol won a scholarship to the Carnegie Institute of Technology in Pittsburgh.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] While working as a produce huckster in 1946, Warhol created a series of pen-and-ink drawings satirizing his customers and documenting social contrasts encountered during his route, from affluent to working-class families.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] His illustrations depicted everyday interactions and behaviors, including demands from "new rich" customers and chaotic scenes involving families and children.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] The series won one of the annual Leisser Art Fund awards, valued at $40, which were given annually to Carnegie Tech students for the best visual representations of their summer activities.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] Warhol described this job as a "wonderful experience" and said that "people are funny," offering an early indication of his interest in observing everyday behavior and social interaction.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] As a student, Warhol worked part-time as a window dresser at Horne's department store and was reportedly threatened with expulsion on several occasions due to his attendance record.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] He also served as art director of the student art magazine, *Cano*, illustrating a cover in 1948 and a full-page interior illustration in 1949.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] These are believed to be his first two published artworks.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] Warhol earned a Bachelor of Fine Arts in pictorial design in 1949.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] After graduating from the Carnegie Institute of Technology in June 1949, Warhol moved to New York City with his classmate Philip Pearlstein.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] They lived in a sixth-floor walk-up tenement building on St.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] Mark's Place near Tompkins Square Park in the East Village.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] On his second day in New York, Warhol visited Tina Fredericks, the art director of *Glamour* magazine, whom he had met during a brief visit to the city the previous year.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] He presented a portfolio of work completed at the Carnegie Institute of Technology, which Fredericks received favorably, purchasing a small $10 drawing of an orchestra for her personal collection.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] She subsequently commissioned Warhol to produce shoe illustrations; after more than one attempt, his drawings were accepted.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] *Glamour* published a page of Warhol's shoe illustrations along with several pages of people climbing the "ladder of success," accompanying the major feature "What Is Success?,"—a package of six articles by Katherine Sonntag, Hazel M.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] Wood, Margot Clarke, Patricia Curtain, Marya Mannes, and Elizabeth Weston.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] The publication marked the beginning of his career as a commercial artist.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] Warhol was hired by prominent fashion magazines, including *Glamour*, *Mademoiselle*, *Vogue*, and *Harper's Bazaar*, and produced a prolific body of advertisements throughout the 1950s.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] During this period, gallerist Alexander Iolas is often credited with discovering Warhol and organizing his first solo exhibition, *Andy Warhol: Fifteen Drawings Based on the Writings of Truman Capote*, at the Hugo Gallery in New York in 1952.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] In May 1952, while working as a freelance artist, Warhol won the Art Directors Club Medal in its annual exhibition of advertising and editorial art for his drawing promoting CBS Radio's *Nation's Nightmare* documentary series.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] Warhol would be featured in the exhibition every year but one over the following decade.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] Between 1953 and 1954, he also designed several covers for *Interiors* magazine.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] In 1954, Warhol exhibited his work on multiple occasions at Vito Giallo's Loft Gallery in New York.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] Within a year, Warhol—then working out of his railroad apartment on East 34th Street—invited Giallo to become his first paid studio assistant.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] In 1955, Warhol began designing advertisements for the shoe manufacturer Israel Miller.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] Photographer John Coplans recalled that "nobody drew shoes the way Andy did.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] Miller attracted considerable attention and earned him the Art Directors Club Award for Distinctive Merit in 1956.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] They sold for $50 to $225 apiece when they were presented at the Bodley Gallery in New York in December 1956.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] In 1956, the Museum of Modern Art (MoMA) politely declined Warhol's gift of his drawing *Shoe*, citing limited storage space and asking him to retrieve it.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] Nevertheless, that same year one of his shoe drawings was included in MoMA's *Recent Drawings U.S.A.* group exhibition, marking Warhol's first museum showing.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] That year, he traveled around the world with his friend, production designer Charles Lisanby, studying art and culture in several countries.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] While in Kyoto, Japan, Warhol drew a stylized portrait of business tycoon Madame Helena Rubinstein.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] Warhol habitually used the expedient of tracing photographs projected with an epidiascope.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] Using prints by Edward Wallowitch, the photographs would undergo a subtle transformation during Warhol's often cursory tracing of contours and hatching of shadows.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] Warhol used Wallowitch's photograph *Young Man Smoking a Cigarette* (c.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] 1956) for a 1958 design for a book cover he submitted to Simon and Schuster for the Walter Ross pulp novel *The Immortal*, and later used others for his series of paintings.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] To promote himself as an artist, Warhol produced and distributed self-published books of his illustrations, including *25 Cats Name Sam and One Blue Pussy* (1957) and *A Gold Book* (1957), which he gave to potential clients and contacts to generate work.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] He frequently incorporated calligraphy by his mother, Julia Warhol, to accompany his drawings.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] With the rapid expansion of the record industry, RCA Records hired Warhol to design album covers and promotional materials.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] By the late 1950s, he was also working for high-end advertising clients, including Tiffany & Co.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] At a time when traditional artists rarely purchased the work of their peers, Warhol actively collected it.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] To survive, gallery artists typically did commercial work, such as window displays, and avoided using their real names because it was frowned upon.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] In contrast, Warhol gained recognition as a commercial artist, which caused tension with other artists.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] In 1960, Warhol purchased a Victorian townhouse at 1342 Lexington Avenue, now part of the Hardenbergh/Rhinelander Historic District, in the Carnegie Hill neighborhood of Manhattan.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] He used the house as both a residence and a studio, and his mother lived in the basement apartment.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] That April, his pop paintings were exhibited for the first time in the window display of the Bonwit Teller department store on Fifth Avenue at 57th Street.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] Five paintings based on comic strips and newspaper ads served as the backdrop for mannequins wearing spring dresses: *Saturday's Popeye*, *Little King*, *Superman*, *Before and After*, and *Advertisement*.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] In 1961, Warhol sold paintings directly to collector Robert Scull and soon attracted major buyers such as Emily Tremaine and Burton Tremaine, but dealer Ivan Karp's efforts failed to secure him gallery representation.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] When Karp introduced him to Leo Castelli, Castelli declined, feeling Warhol's work was too close to that of Roy Lichtenstein and concern over potential conflicts within his roster.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] Out of desperation, Warhol considered returning to the Bodley Gallery, but its director dismissed his new paintings as "ridiculous." Karp subsequently approached Sidney Janis, Richard Bellamy, Martha Jackson, and Robert Elkon, with only Jackson expressing interest in a future exhibition.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] After seeing Claes Oldenburg's storefront installation *The Store* in December 1961, Warhol returned home frustrated, telling friends Ted Carey and Muriel Flatow that his comic-strip paintings no longer felt original enough.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] Determined to create something more distinctive and impactful, he accepted Flatow's tongue-in-cheek suggestion—offered in exchange for $50—that he focus on what he liked most: money.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] Warhol began considering silkscreened images of dollar bills, drawn to the idea of mechanically reproducing currency like counterfeit cash.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] Seeking technical guidance, he turned to Floriano Vecchi of Tiber Press, who introduced him to the basics of silkscreen printing—transferring designs onto acetate, preparing screens, and pulling ink with a squeegee.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] These experiments marked a turning point in Warhol's practice and soon led to some of his earliest silkscreen works.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] Dealer Allan Stone took several works on consignment and offered Warhol a three-man exhibition alongside Robert Indiana and James Rosenquist, but all three artists declined, each holding out for a solo show.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] As Pop art gained momentum in New York in 1962, Warhol remained without major gallery representation, increasingly determined to secure his place within the emerging movement.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] In May 1962, Warhol was featured in *Time* magazine's article "The Slice-of-Cake School," alongside Lichtenstein, Rosenquist, and Wayne Thiebaud.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] At the time, he was working on his *Campbell's Soup Cans* (1961–62) paintings and had completed sixteen of them.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] When Los Angeles dealer Irving Blum visited, he was surprised to learn that Warhol lacked gallery representation.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] With an opening available in July, Blum offered him a solo exhibition at the Ferus Gallery.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] Warhol sent 32 canvases to Los Angeles, each depicting a different variety of Campbell's Soup.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] The exhibition opened on July 9, 1962, marking his West Coast debut.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] During the run of the exhibition, a forthcoming December show at the Martha Jackson Gallery was canceled due to concerns about negative repercussions.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] Despite the cancellation, Jackson's assistant John Weber sold ten Warhol paintings that had been taken on consignment.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] In July 1962, Warhol's *Big Campbell's Soup Can with Can Opener (Vegetable)* (1962) became the first of his soup-can paintings to enter a museum exhibition when it was shown at the Wadsworth Atheneum in Hartford, Connecticut.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] The following month, his painting *S&H Green Stamps* (1962) was included in the exhibition *New Painting of Common Objects* at the Pasadena Art Museum in Pasadena, California.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] The show featured works drawn from commercial labels, consumer goods, and advertising imagery, contributing to the movement's early critical recognition.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] Warhol was invited by art dealer Sidney Janis to participate in the October 1962 exhibition, *The New Realists: An Exhibition of Factual Painting & Sculpture* at her New York gallery.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] Warhol exhibited his 1962 paintings *200 Soup Cans*, *Big Campbell's Soup Can 19c (Beef Noodle)*, and *Do It Yourself (Flowers)*.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] The exhibition was widely seen as a turning point in the acceptance of Pop art; *The New Yorker* likened its impact on the New York art world to an "earthquake," while *The Kansas City Star* newspaper ran the headline, "Which Way Is Modern Art Going?
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] Filmmaker Emile de Antonio introduced Warhol to dealer Eleanor Ward of the Stable Gallery, who agreed to give him a solo exhibition in exchange for a painting of a two-dollar bill.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] Warhol's first solo New York Pop show opened there on November 6, 1962.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] The exhibition contained eighteen new works, including *Marilyn Monroe Twenty Times*, *Flavor Marilyns*, *Gold Marilyn Monroe*, *129 Die in Jet!*, *Red Elvis*, *Troy Donahue*, *100 Soup Cans*, *100 Coke Bottles*, and *100 Dollar Bills*.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] In December 1962, the MoMA hosted a symposium on Pop art, during which artists such as Warhol were attacked for "capitulating" to consumerism.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] Critics were appalled by Warhol's open acceptance of market culture, which set the tone for his reception.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] The next year, Warhol formed The Druds, a short-lived avant-garde noise band that included figures from the New York minimal art and proto-conceptual art scenes, including Larry Poons, La Monte Young, Walter De Maria, Jasper Johns, Claes Oldenburg, and Lucas Samaras.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] In January 1963, Warhol rented his first studio, an old firehouse at 159 East 87th Street, where he produced his *Elvis* series, including *Eight Elvises* (1963) and *Triple Elvis* (1963).
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] These works, along with a series of portraits of Elizabeth Taylor, were exhibited later that year at his second exhibition at the Ferus Gallery in Los Angeles.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] By 1964, Warhol had relocated his studio to 231 East 47th Street, which became known as the Factory.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] Warhol used assistants to increase his productivity, and these collaborations would remain a defining aspect of his working methods throughout his career.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] During this period, poet Gerard Malanga assisted him with the production of silkscreens and films at the Factory, which was covered in aluminium foil and silver paint by Billy Name in 1964.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] Warhol was among the artists commissioned to create an artwork for the New York State Pavilion at the 1964 World's Fair in Queens, New York.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] He created the mural *Thirteen Most Wanted Men* (1964), which was painted over after government officials objected to the images before the fair opened in April 1964.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] That spring, Warhol had his second exhibition at the Stable Gallery in the spring of 1964, which featured sculptures of commercial boxes stacked and scattered throughout the space to resemble a warehouse.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] For the exhibition, Warhol custom ordered wooden boxes and silkscreened graphics onto them.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] The sculptures of commercial cartons—Brillo Soap Pads, Del Monte Peach Halves, Heinz Tomato Ketchup, Kellogg's Corn Flakes, Campbell's Tomato Juice, and Mott's Apple Juice—sold for $200 to $400 depending on the size of the box.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] A pivotal event in Warhol's career was *The American Supermarket* exhibition at Paul Bianchini's Upper East Side gallery in October 1964.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] The show was presented as a typical small supermarket environment, except that everything in it—from the produce, canned goods, meat, and paintings on the wall—was created by prominent Pop artists of the time.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] Warhol designed a paper shopping bag and contributed his box sculptures along with a *Campbell's Soup Can* painting, and genuine signed Campbell's soup cans.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] The exhibit was one of the first mass events that directly confronted the general public with both Pop art and the perennial question of what art is.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] In November 1964, Warhol's first *Flowers* series was exhibited at the Leo Castelli Gallery in New York.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] In May 1965, his second *Flowers* series, which had more sizes and color variation that the previous, was shown at Galerie Ileana Sonnabend in Paris.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] During this trip Warhol announced that he was retiring from painting to focus on film.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] Warhol made a conscious decision to oppose conventional painting, stating that he no longer believed in painting.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] Later that year, Warhol's first solo museum exhibition was held at the Institute of Contemporary Art, Philadelphia in October 1965.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] In response to art dealer Ivan Karp's suggestion to paint cows, Warhol produced *Cow*, screenprints on wallpaper for his April 1966 exhibition at the Leo Castelli Gallery.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] In 1966, Warhol underwent a transitional period as he sought to expand his filmmaking activities and increase his income.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] He had begun managing the experimental rock band the Velvet Underground, allowing them to rehearse at the Factory.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] By February, Warhol had filmed the band rehearsing at the Factory for *Symphony of Sound* (1966).
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] The group also provided soundtracks for two of his 1966 films, *Hedy* (1966) and *More Milk, Yvette* (1966), and performed in a multimedia production titled Andy Warhol, Up-Tight, staged nightly at the underground film center Cinémathèque.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] Warhol also became involved with the East Village discotheque the Dom, later known as the Electric Circus.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] After learning that Jackie Cassen and Rudy Stern had rented the Polish dance hall Polsky Dom Narodny Dom on St.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] Mark's Place, Warhol and filmmaker Paul Morrissey quickly subleased the venue for a month and transformed it into a multimedia performance space.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] The interior was painted white to accommodate film and slide projections, while mirrored disco balls, strobe lights, spotlights, and multiple projectors were installed to create an immersive environment.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] The venue became the home base for the Velvet Underground and the site of Warhol's Exploding Plastic Inevitable performances in April 1966.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] The performances were successful and Warhol took the show on the road, touring cities across the United States and Canada throughout 1966 into 1967.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] As the band's manager, Warhol also financed their debut album, *The Velvet Underground & Nico* (1967).
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] In November 1966, Warhol was hired by the Abraham & Straus department store in Brooklyn to promote the Mars Manufacturing Company's "Paint-your-own-dress" collection, which featured white paper dresses sold with watercolors and a paintbrush.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] During a live demonstration at the store, Warhol painted two dresses using Nico as his model; the dresses were donated to the Brooklyn Museum.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] His remark that "everyone will be famous for 15 minutes" first appeared in a 1967 *Time* magazine article and became closely associated with the Factory scene.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] To finance his film productions, Warhol began going on college lecture tours, where he screened some of his underground films and answered audience questions.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] Warhol sent actor Allen Midgette to impersonate him during a West Coast college tour in October 1967.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] Warhol reimbursed the four institutions where he did not appear and returned to the campuses in 1968.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] Around this time, Warhol met Fred Hughes, then working for the Menil Foundation, who soon became closely involved in his activities.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] At the time, Warhol had largely paused painting, but he resumed work shortly thereafter, producing the *Big* *Electric Chair* paintings for his retrospective at the Moderna Museet in Stockholm in 1968.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] Hughes quickly took on a central role in both Warhol's artistic and film projects, arranging a commission from the de Menils for Warhol to film a sunset as part of a project for the restoration of a bombed church in Texas.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] The remaining funds from that commission were used to finance *Lonesome Cowboys* (1968), which was filmed in Arizona.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] On June 3, 1968, radical feminist writer Valerie Solanas shot Warhol and Mario Amaya, art critic and curator, at the Factory.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] Solanas had been a marginal figure in the Factory scene before the shooting.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] She authored the *SCUM Manifesto*, a separatist feminist tract that advocated the elimination of men; and appeared in the Warhol film *I, a Man* (1967).
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] Amaya received only minor injuries and was released from the hospital later the same day.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] Warhol was seriously wounded by the attack and barely survived: he remained in hospital for nearly two months.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] Solanas turned herself in to the police a few hours after the attack and said that Warhol "had too much control over my life." She was subsequently diagnosed with paranoid schizophrenia and eventually sentenced to three years in prison.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] Jed Johnson, an assistant who was present at the Factory during the shooting, visited Warhol daily at the hospital, and the two developed an intimate relationship.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] Shortly after Warhol was discharged, Johnson moved in with him to aid in his recovery and to help care for his ailing mother.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] During Warhol's hospitalization that summer, Morrissey assumed primary filmmaking responsibilities and directed his first film, *Flesh* (1968), starring Joe Dallesandro.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] The assassination attempt had a profound effect on Warhol's life and art.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] Complications from a second operation the following year left his abdominal muscles improperly repaired, requiring him to wear a surgical corset for the rest of his life to prevent his stomach from distending when he ate.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] The Factory became more regulated, and Warhol focused on making it a structured business enterprise.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] He credited Morrissey with transforming the Factory into a "regular office." In August 1968, Warhol made an appearance in court after Phillip "Fufu" Van Scoy Smith, an investor in a canceled film adaptation of the Charlotte Brontë novel *Jane Eyre*, sued him for $80,000.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] A legal battle ensued for two years, ending after the backer failed to show up in court.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] Warhol reemerged on the public social scene that fall.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] In September 1968, Warhol and Ultra Violet attended a party celebrating the completion of the film *Midnight Cowboy*.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] The film includes a party scene featuring members of the Factory that was shot during Warhol's hospitalization.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] That same month, Warhol hosted a party at the Factory for the release of Nico's album *The Marble Index*.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] Warhol, Viva, and Ultra Violet also appeared on the cover of *The New York Times* *Magazine* on November 10, 1968.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] In February 1969, Warhol and his entourage traveled to Los Angeles to discuss a prospective movie deal with Columbia Pictures.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] Warhol, who had always had an interest in photography, used a Polaroid camera to document his recuperation after the shooting.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] A few of his photographs were published in the May 1969 edition of *Esquire* magazine.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] He would become well known for always carrying his Polaroid camera to chronicle his encounters.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] Eventually, he used instant photography as the basis for his silkscreen portraits when he resumed painting in the 1970s.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] After the release of the erotic film *Blue Movie* (1969), Warhol rented the Fortune Theater at 62 East 4th Street, where he screened male pornographic films from June 25 to August 5, 1969.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] The project was managed by Gerard Malanga under his business, Poetry on Film.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] The theater was called "Andy Warhol's Theater: Boys to Adore Galore." Morrissey came up with the idea to rent the theater and set the admission price at $5.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] Warhol and British journalist John Wilcock founded *Interview* magazine in the fall of 1969.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] The magazine was initially published as *inter/VIEW: A Monthly Film Journal*.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] It was revamped a few years later and came to represent Warhol's social life and fascination with celebrity.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] In 1969, Warhol received an invitation to curate an exhibition using items from the permanent collection of the Rhode Island School of Design Museum (RISD Museum) in Providence.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] In October 1969, the exhibition *Raid the Icebox* opened at Rice University's Institute for the Arts in Houston.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] In 1970, the show traveled to the Isaac Delgado Museum in New Orleans before arriving at the RISD Museum.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] Compared to the success and scandal of Warhol's work in the 1960s, the early 1970s were much quieter years, as he became more entrepreneurial.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] He was generally regarded as quiet, shy and a meticulous observer.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] Art critic Robert Hughes called him "the white mole of Union Square".
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] His fashion evolved from what Warhol called his "leather look" to his "Brooks Brothers look," which included a Brooks Brothers shirt and tie, DeNoyer blazer, and Levi jeans.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] As Warhol continued to forge into filmmaking, he had established himself as "one of the most celebrated and well-known Pop art figures to emerge from the sixties." The Pasadena Art Museum organized a retrospective of his work in 1970.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] The show traveled to the Museum of Contemporary Art, Chicago; Stedelijk Van Abbemuseum, Eindhoven; Musée d'Art Moderne de la Ville de Paris; Tate Gallery, London; and Whitney Museum of American Art, New York.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] The Whitney exhibition in 1971 distinctly featured Warhol's *Cow* (1966) wallpaper as the backdrop for his paintings.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] Meanwhile, Warhol produced the play *Andy Warhol's Pork*, which opened at New York's La MaMa Experimental Theatre in May 1971.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] A few months later, the controversial production was brought to the Roundhouse in London.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] Warhol also came up with the cover concept and did the photography for the Rolling Stones' album *Sticky Fingers* (1971), which features a close-up image of a man's crotch in jeans with a real zipper.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] He received a Grammy nomination for Best Album Cover at the 14th Annual Grammy Awards in 1972.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] In late 1971, Warhol and his business partner Paul Morrissey purchased Eothen, an oceanfront estate in Montauk, New York on Long Island.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] They began renting the main house on the property in 1972.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] Lee Radziwill, Jackie Kennedy, the Rolling Stones, Elizabeth Taylor, Truman Capote, and Halston were among the estate's guests.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] In 1972, Warhol planned the Halston runway presentation at the Coty Awards.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] Although Warhol was considered to be apolitical, he participated in an exhibition with the poster *Vote McGovern* (1972) in an effort to raise funds for George McGovern's 1972 presidential campaign.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] In October 1972, Warhol's work was included in the inaugural show at the Art Museum of South Texas in Corpus Christi, Texas.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] The following month, Warhol's *Mao* screenprints debuted at the Leo Castelli Gallery in New York.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] In November 1972, Warhol and his live-in boyfriend Jed Johnson acquired a dachshund puppy they named Archie.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] Warhol doted on Archie and took him everywhere: to the studio, parties, restaurants, and on trips to Europe.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] He created portraits of Johnson, Archie, and Amos—a second dachshund that joined their family a few years later.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] In 1974, the couple moved into a Neo-Georgian townhouse at 57 East 66th Street in Manhattan's Lenox Hill neighborhood.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] By this time, Warhol's public presence had increased significantly due to his attendance at parties.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] Warhol began traveling more frequently to Europe during this period and developed a particular fondness for Paris after filming *L'Amour* (1972) around the city.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] He maintained an apartment on the Left Bank, on Rue du Cherche-Midi, which he shared with his business manager Fred Hughes.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] While in Paris, Warhol and his circle socialized with members of the city's jet set, including Karl Lagerfeld, Yves Saint Laurent, Loulou de la Falaise, and Paloma Picasso.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] This lifestyle shift has been attributed in part to Hughes, who sought to cultivate a more polished public image for Warhol and to position the Factory as an international social and artistic presence.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] Warhol designed the sets for the Broadway musical *Man on the Moon* by John Philips of the Mamas & the Papas, which opened in January 1975 at the Little Theatre in New York.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] In May 1975, Warhol attended President Gerald Ford's state dinner in honor of the Shah of Iran, Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, at the White House.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] In September 1975, he went on an eight-city U.S. book tour for his book *The Philosophy of Andy Warhol (From A to B & Back Again)*, followed by stops in Italy, France, and England.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] In June 1975, the Baltimore Museum of Art mounted a major exhibition showcasing works from various periods of his career.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] In 1976, Warhol and painter Jamie Wyeth were commissioned to paint each other's portraits by the Coe Kerr Gallery in Manhattan.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] That year, Warhol traveled to Iran to do a portrait of Empress Farah Pahlavi.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] He returned to the Middle East in January 1977, when he traveled to Kuwait for the opening of his exhibition at Salat Al Funoon in Dahiyat Abdullah Al-Salem.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] The opening of Studio 54 on April 1977 ushered in a new era in New York City nightlife.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] Warhol was a regular and was often seen partying with his friends Halston, Bianca Jagger, and Liza Minnelli.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] Around this time, Warhol was taking explicit photographs of men—referred to as "landscapes"—for what became known as the *Torsos* and *Sex Parts* series.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] Most of the men were street hustlers and male prostitutes brought to the Factory by Halston's lover Victor Hugo.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] This caused tension in Warhol's relationship with Johnson, who did not approve of his friendship with Hugo.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] "When Studio 54 opened things changed with Andy.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] That was New York when it was at the height of its most decadent period, and I didn't take part.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] I never liked that scene, I was never comfortable. … Andy was just wasting his time, and it was really upsetting. … He just spent his time with the most ridiculous people," said Johnson.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] In May 1977, Warhol and entrepreneur Geoffrey Leeds announced plans for the "Andy-Mat," a modern automat-style restaurant on Madison Avenue in New York City.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] Designed as a self-service dining space, the 115-seat restaurant was to feature pre-prepared frozen foods alongside luxury items such as champagne, served through pneumatic tubes, and a waitstaff would deliver orders.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] Warhol had total artistic control over the design, including the logo, flatware, and décor, with interiors incorporating whimsical, childlike motifs.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] Menu items, priced between $1 and $5.75, ranged from comfort foods like shepherd's pie to desserts and mini omelets.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] While the project aimed to blend everyday dining with artistic spectacle and potentially expand internationally, the restaurant was never realized.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] In June 1977, Warhol was invited to a special reception honoring the "Inaugural Artists" who had contributed prints to the Jimmy Carter presidential campaign.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] That year, Warhol was commissioned by art collector Richard Weisman to create *Athletes*, ten portraits consisting of the leading athletes of the day, for an exhibition that opened at New York's Coe Kerr Gallery in December 1977.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] In 1979, Warhol formed a publishing company, Andy Warhol Books, which was an imprint of Grosset & Dunlap.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] In October 1979, he released the photography book *Exposures*.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] The following month, he embarked on a three-week book tour before the Whitney Museum of American Art mounted the exhibition *Andy Warhol: Portraits of the 70s*.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] The exhibition showcased Warhol's portrait commissions of the decade—including Yves Saint Laurent, Gianni Agnelli, Marella Agnelli, David Hockney, Roy Lichtenstein, Brooke Hayward, Carolina Herrera, Mick Jagger, and Liza Minnelli.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] In March 1980, Warhol released his memoir *POPism: The Warhol* *'60s*, a retrospective account of his 1960s career and the cultural environment of the Factory.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] That year, his series *Ten Portraits of Jews of the Twentieth Century* drew a wide range of responses, some of them strongly critical.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] Warhol also co-founded the New York Academy of Art in 1980, an institution dedicated to restoring traditional approaches to artistic training.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] During this period, Warhol developed his *Myths* series (1981), reimagining cultural icons such as Mickey Mouse, Superman, and Uncle Sam.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] His longstanding fascination with celebrity and Hollywood glamour also persisted; he once remarked, "I love Los Angeles.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] Everything's plastic, but I love plastic.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] I want to be plastic." Following the end of his relationship with Jed Johnson, his only sustained romantic partnership, Warhol experienced a period of depression and significant weight loss.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] He shifted his attention to modeling, signing with the Zoli Agency in 1981, and was later represented by Ford Models.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] In 1981, Warhol collaborated with Peter Sellars and Lewis Allen on a project titled *A No Man Show*, a traveling stage production featuring a life-sized animatronic robot modeled after Warhol.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] Known as the *Andy Warhol Robot*, the figure was designed to read from Warhol's diaries as part of the performance, reflecting his long-standing interest in mechanization and authorship.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] In 1982, Warhol created a limited edition of 100 silkscreen portraits of actress Jane Fonda to support the California State Assembly campaign of her husband, Tom Hayden.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] Donated to the campaign, the signed prints were sold for $2,000 each.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] In 1983, Warhol was commissioned to design a poster commemorating the centennial of the Brooklyn Bridge, which he contributed to the New York Art Expo that year.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] He also produced a series of *Endangered Species* (1983) screenprints for *Warhol's Animals: Species at Risk*, an exhibition held in April 1983 at the American Museum of Natural History in New York City.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] Ahead of the 1984 Sarajevo Winter Olympics, Warhol participated in the poster campaign by contributing the lithograph *Speed Skater* (1983).
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] He also supported artists in the downtown art scene such as Jean-Michel Basquiat, Keith Haring, Kenny Scharf, and Stefano Castronovo.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] In September 1985, Warhol's joint exhibition with Basquiat, *Paintings*, opened to negative reviews at the Tony Shafrazi Gallery.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] That same month, despite his apprehension, Warhol's silkscreen series *Reigning Queens* (1985) was exhibited at the Leo Castelli Gallery.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] Later that year, he collaborated with Haring to design the poster for the 1986 Montreux Jazz Festival in Switzerland, which was also used for the 1986 Montreux-Detroit Jazz Festival in Detroit.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] In April 1986, Warhol's exhibition *10 Status of Liberty* (1986) opened at the Galerie Lavignes-Bastille in Paris in conjunction with the centennial of the Statue of Liberty, presenting the symbol of freedom in camouflage and layered colors.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] The following month, one of the paintings was used for the cover *New York* magazine.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] That same year, he completed a new series of *Self-Portraits* (1986), characterized by his "fright wig" and stark contrasts, which premiered at London's Anthony d'Offay Gallery in July 1986.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] In January 1987, Warhol traveled to Milan for the opening of his last exhibition, *Il Cenacolo (The Last Supper)*, at the Palazzo delle Stelline.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] The next month, Warhol modeled with jazz musician Miles Davis for Koshin Satoh's fashion show at the Tunnel in New York City on February 17, 1987.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] Warhol was initially diagnosed with a gallstone in 1973, but adamantly rejected surgery because he feared hospitals.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] When he was insistent about avoiding surgery, his physician Denton Cox attempted to obtain an experimental medication from Japan.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] The artist also sought guidance from a chiropractor and nutritionist, who suggested that he wear a small crystal.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] Dehydrated and unable to eat, Warhol was in excruciating pain by February 1987.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] Warhol was admitted to New York Hospital in Manhattan on February 20, and he underwent gallbladder surgery on February 21.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] His surgeon Bjorn Thorbjarnarson found his gallbladder "on the verge of perforating" and in danger of "spilling the infection into (Warhol's) belly." Warhol was awake and able to walk about, make phone calls, and watch television when both of his doctors visited him after the four-hour operation.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] His private nurse, Min Cho, saw his growing pallor at 4:30 the following morning, but she did not call the hospital's cardiac-arrest team until 5:45 am, when he was "unresponsive" and turning blue.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] He was pronounced dead at 6:31 a.m. from sudden cardiac arrhythmia.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] Warhol's brothers took his body back to Pittsburgh, where an open-casket wake was held at the Thomas P.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] The solid bronze casket had gold-plated rails and white upholstery.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] Warhol was dressed in a black cashmere suit, a paisley tie, and a platinum wig.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] He was laid out holding a small prayer book and a red rose.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] A half-hour funeral liturgy in English and Slavonic was led by Monsignor Peter Tay at the Holy Ghost Byzantine Catholic Church on Pittsburgh's North Side on February 26, 1987.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] After the liturgy, the casket, covered with white roses and asparagus ferns, was driven to St.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] John the Baptist Byzantine Catholic Cemetery in Bethel Park, a south suburb of Pittsburgh, where Warhol was buried near his parents.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] The priest said a brief prayer at the graveside and sprinkled holy water on the casket.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] Before the casket was lowered, Warhol's close friend Paige Powell tossed copies of the February and March issues of *Interview* magazine along with a bottle of Estée Lauder's Beautiful Eau de Parfum into his grave.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] A memorial service for Warhol was held at St.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] Patrick's Cathedral in Manhattan on April 1, 1987.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] It was attended by over 2,000 people, including Warhol collaborators and numerous celebrities such as Raquel Welch, Debbie Harry, Liza Minnelli, Claus von Bülow, and Calvin Klein, among others.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] Eulogies were given by his friends John Richardson and Yoko Ono.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] Afterwards, there was a luncheon at the Diamond Horseshoe nightclub beneath the Paramount Hotel.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] In April 1987, the New York State Health Department released a report that Warhol was given inadequate care by New York Hospital from the time he was admitted until the hours before his death.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] These included not performing the appropriate work-up tests prior to surgery, giving Warhol antibiotics to which he may have experienced an allergic response, causing him to become overhydrated, and repeatedly failing to take accurate notes on his chart.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] There were no issues with the procedure itself, according to the report.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] In response, the hospital dismissed the private nurse who had been employed to care for Warhol and penalized the staff nurse who had been tasked with overseeing her.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] However, the hospital claimed that the nursing deficiencies were not significant enough to cause Warhol's death.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] In December 1991, Warhol's family sued the hospital in the New York Supreme Court for inadequate care, before judge Ira Gammerman, saying that the arrhythmia was caused by improper care and water intoxication.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] The malpractice case was quickly settled out of court; Warhol's family received an undisclosed sum of money.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p01] Prior to his surgery, doctors expected Warhol to survive, though a re-evaluation of the case about thirty years after his death showed many indications that Warhol's surgery was in fact riskier than originally thought.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] Although Warhol is best known for his work in printmaking, particularly silkscreen, he was also a highly skilled illustrator and draughtsman.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] His early drawings on paper convey a sense of ease and immediacy, shaped by the "blotted line" technique he pioneered as a student at Carnegie Tech.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] Warhol achieved the blotted-line effect through a simple but deliberate process.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] He taped a penciled drawing to a sheet of smooth Strathmore board, traced sections of the image in ink, and while the ink was still wet, pressed the sheets together to transfer the design.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] Because the ink dried quickly, he worked in stages—lifting and re-inking the drawing until the entire image was transferred—producing irregular, variable lines in a process akin to rudimentary printmaking.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] He embraced the accidental blots and breaks created by this method, never making corrections, and often applied pastel washes of Dr.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] He sometimes used photographs to trace for his drawings.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] His illustration style was instantly recognizable, marked by a casual sophistication often described as a lighter, more playful take on Ben Shahn.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] Among the best known of these early works are his shoe illustrations for I.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] Some of his personal drawings were self-published in small booklets, including *Yum, Yum, Yum* (food-themed), *Ho, Ho, Ho* (Christmas-themed), and *Shoes, Shoes, Shoes*.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] His most critically acclaimed book of illustrations is *A Gold Book*, a collection of drawings of young men, distinguished by the use of gold leaf decorating its pages.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] The drawings from his later years demonstrate the skill and technique that have been refined over the course of his career.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] In the early 1960s, the Pop art movement was an experimental form that several artists were independently adopting.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] Warhol, who would be dubbed the "Pope of Pop Art" and "King of Pop," turned to this new style, where popular subjects could be part of the artist's palette.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] He experimented with his artistic style and painting techniques before he became synonymous with the movement.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] His early paintings feature images taken from cartoons and advertisements, hand-painted with paint drips.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] Those drips emulated the style of Abstract expressionists such as Willem de Kooning.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] His first Pop art paintings were displayed in April 1961, serving as the backdrop for the New York Department Store Bonwit Teller's window display.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] In 1962, Warhol adopted the silkscreen print process as a technique for making paintings to make a more "assembly-line effect." For this process, a photograph was enlarged and transferred in glue onto a silk mesh.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] Ink was then rolled across the screen with a squeegee, passing through the unsealed areas of the mesh, thereby transferring the image onto the canvas.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] Warhol had several assistants throughout his career, including Gerard Malanga, Ronnie Cutrone, and Jay Shriver, who helped him produced his silkscreen, following his directions to make different varitions.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] For his first major exhibition in 1962, Warhol painted his celebrated cans of Campbell's soup, which he claimed to have had for lunch for 20 years.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] Warhol began to make paintings of everyday objects such as Coca-Cola bottles, dollar bills , trading stamps, and more gruesome subjects such as images of suicide, electric chairs, and car crashes, as in the *Death and Disaster* (1962–67) series.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] He also painted portraits of icons such as Warren Beatty, Marilyn Monroe, Elizabeth Taylor, and Jackie Kennedy.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] His work became popular and controversial.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] Throughout the 1960s, Warhol repeatedly returned to Marilyn Monroe as a subject, creating works such as *Gold Marilyn Monroe* (1962), serial images including *Marilyn Diptych* (1962), the *Flavor Marilyns* (1962)—named for their color and Life Savers candy flavors.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] In 1964, four of his new larger Marilyn canvases were famously shot by performance artist Dorothy Podber, resulting in the *Shot Marilyns*.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] In 1967, Warhol established Factory Additions as his printmaking and publishing enterprise, issuing portfolios of ten images in editions of 250.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] In 1970, some of the acetate films used to produce some of Warhol's screenprints were taken to Europe, where they were used to create a new series of editions published under the name "Sunday B.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] Morning." Produced in Belgium using the same color references as the original Factory prints, the editions included versions of Warhol's *Marilyn Monroe*, *Flowers, Campbell's Soup I, Campbell's Soup Cans II*, and *Dollar Bill* images.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] In the 1970s, Warhol evolved into a portraiture artist, painting commissioned portraits of celebrities and socialites.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] The last portrait he made at the old Factory at 33 Union Square West, in 1974, was of his mother, Julia Warhola, who had died two years earlier.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] In the new Factory at 860 Broadway, he left behind the finger-painting and gestural complexity of his 1972–74 works for a cleaner, more streamlined style—echoing the shift from the old studio's clutter to the new one's openness.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] Many of the portraits Warhol produced between 1975 and 1976, share a soft, pastel look, with distant eyes under washes of azure, mint, or lavender.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] This style defined his portrayals of Mick Jagger, Joe MacDonald, Roy Lichtenstein, Marilyn Karp, Marcia Weisman, and Tina Freeman.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] Warhol wasn't only painting commissioned portraits—though some non-portrait works were still dealer-commissioned before he began them.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] His studio production returned to mid-sixties levels, with the same intensity and volume.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] After the *Mao* series (1972–73), he created *Hand Colored Flowers* (1974), a portfolio of 10 flower prints, silkscreened in black and hand watercolored.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] In 1975, Warhol completed the *Ladies and Gentlemen* series, followed by *Cats and Dogs* in 1976 and the *Skulls* series later that year.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] He subsequently began working on *Hammer and Sickle* (1976–77).
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] In 1977, he debuted his *Torsos* and *Athletes* series, and then began *Oxidation* (1977–78) also known as "piss paintings," which were abstract works that Warhol created by exposing a layer of metallic paint to urine, and *Shadows* (1978–79).
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] In 1979, Warhol was commissioned to paint a BMW M1 Group 4 racing version for the fourth installment of the BMW Art Car project.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] He was initially asked to paint a BMW 320i in 1978, but the car model was changed, and it didn't qualify for the race that year.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] Warhol was the first artist to paint directly onto the automobile himself instead of letting technicians transfer a scale-model design to the car.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] Reportedly, it took him only 23 minutes to paint the entire car.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] Racecar drivers Hervé Poulain, Manfred Winkelhock and Marcel Mignot drove the car at the 1979 24 Hours of Le Mans.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] In 1979, Warhol began his *Reversals* and *Retrospectives* series, revisiting earlier subjects such as Marilyn Monroe, Mao Zedong, and his disaster imagery.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] During the 1980s, art dealer Ronald Feldman often handled the legal and licensing issues surrounding Warhol's print and painting projects, working closely with Warhol and his business manager Fred Hughes.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] Feldman commissioned several portfolios, including *Ten Portraits of Jews of the Twentieth Century* (1980), *Myths* (1981), and *Endangered Species* (1983).
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] In 1983, Warhol began collaborating with artists Jean-Michel Basquiat and Francesco Clemente.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] Warhol and Basquiat created a series of more than 50 large collaborative works between 1984 and 1985.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] Late in his career, Warhol was commissioned by gallerist Alexander Iolas to produce work based on Leonardo da Vinci's *The Last Supper*.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] His *Last Supper* (1985–86) series is the largest series of religious-themed works by an American artist.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] In the period just before his death, Warhol was also working on *Cars* (1986), a series of paintings for Mercedes-Benz, and *Moonwalk* (1987), prints from a proposed history of television series.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] In 1985, Warhol used Amiga computers to generate digital art, including the short film *You Are the One*.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] He also did a demonstration on live TV with singer Debbie Harry as a model.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] Warhol's most well-known sculptures are his *Brillo Boxes*—silkscreen ink on wood replicas of the large branded cardboard boxes used to hold 24 packages of Brillo soap pads.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] The original Brillo design was by commercial artist James Harvey.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] Warhol's *Brillo Boxes* were part of a series of "grocery carton" works that also included Heinz ketchup and Campbell's tomato juice boxes.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] Other famous works include the *Silver Clouds*—helium filled, silver mylar, pillow-shaped balloons.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] A *Silver Cloud* was included in the traveling exhibition *Air Art* (1968–1969) curated by Willoughby Sharp.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] *Clouds* was also adapted by Warhol for avant-garde choreographer Merce Cunningham's dance piece *RainForest* (1968).
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] Warhol's *Invisible Sculpture* made in 1980 consisted of burglar alarms placed around the perimeter of a room at the Factory and aimed toward an empty center.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] When a visitor stepped into the center point, all the alarms were triggered simultaneously.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] A version of *Invisible Sculpture* without the burglar alarms was installed at New York's Area nightclub in 1984 as part of its "Art" theme.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] During Warhol's lifetime, his work was initially modestly priced.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] In 1965, large paintings from the *Flowers* series sold for approximately $6,000, while smaller versions were available for as little as $400.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] By the 1970s, Warhol had established a lucrative portrait practice, charging $25,000 for a commissioned portrait, with a discounted rate of $40,000 for two portraits.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] Warhol's market began to gain momentum at auction during his lifetime.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] In 1970, *Campbell's Soup Can with Peeling Label* (1962) sold for $60,000 at Parke-Bernet Galleries, then the highest price ever paid at public auction for a work by a living American artist.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] In 1978, *19 Cents* (1962) sold for $95,000—setting a new auction record for Warhol—after having originally been purchased for $1,300 in 1962.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] Following Warhol's death in 1987, the value of his work continued to rise significantly, establishing him as one of the most consistently high-performing artists in the global art market.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] In 2014 alone, Warhol's works generated approximately $569 million at auction, accounting for more than one-sixth of the global art market that year.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] Despite occasional downturns, his market has demonstrated long-term resilience.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] Art dealer Dominique Lévy characterized Warhol's market as "a seesaw being pulled uphill," noting that while prices fluctuate, each successive peak and decline occurs at a higher level than the previous one.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] She attributed this pattern to the continual influx of new collectors, observing that different generations and demographics periodically enter the market, driving renewed demand before stabilizing and giving way to the next cycle of interest.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] Warhol's celebrity imagery commands high prices, and Marilyn Monroe remains one of his most iconic subjects.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] Newhouse Jr. purchased *Orange Marilyn* (1964) at Sotheby's for $17.3 million, setting a new record at the time for the highest price paid for a Warhol work.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] After Newhouse's death in 2017, hedge fund manager Kenneth C.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] Griffin reportedly purchased *Orange Marilyn* in a private sale for approximately $200 million.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] Warhol's market continued to strengthen in the 2000s.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] In 2007, collectors Stefan Edlis and Gael Neeson sold *Turquoise Marilyn* (1964) to financier Steven A.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] Cohen in a private transaction reportedly valued at $80 million.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] In May 2007, *Green Car Crash (Green Burning Car I)* (1963) realized $71.1 million at Christie's, while *Lemon Marilyn* (1962) sold for $28 million in the same auction.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] In November 2009, *200 One Dollar Bills* (1962) sold for $43.8 million at Sotheby's.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] The Elvis series remains among Warhol's most important bodies of work; of the 22 versions produced, eleven are held in museum collections.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] *Eight Elvises* (1963), depicting Elvis Presley in a gunslinger pose, was sold privately in 2008 by Annibale Berlingieri for approximately $100 million.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] Related works have also achieved strong results at auction, including *Double Elvis (Ferus Type)*, which sold for $37 million at Sotheby's in 2012, and *Triple Elvis (Ferus Type)*, which sold for $81.9 million at Christie's in 2014.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] Portraits of Elizabeth Taylor have also been highly sought after.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] In 2007, *Liz (Colored Liz)* (1963), formerly owned by actor Hugh Grant, sold for $23.7 million at Christie's.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] In November 2010, *Men in Her Life* (1962) sold for $63.4 million at Phillips de Pury, while *Coca-Cola (4)* (1962) sold for $35.3 million at Sotheby's.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] 5 (Early Colored Liz)* sold for $26.9 million at Phillips.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] In May 2015, *Silver Liz* (1963, diptych) sold for $28 million, while *Colored Mona Lisa* (1963) achieved $56.2 million at Christie's.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] Warhol's self-portraits have likewise performed strongly at auction.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] In May 2010, a purple self-portrait from 1986, formerly owned by fashion designer Tom Ford, sold for $32.6 million at Sotheby's.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] In May 2011, Warhol's earliest self-portrait from 1963–64 sold for $38.4 million at Christie's, while a red self-portrait from 1986 sold for $27.5 million at the same auction house.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] Several major sales in the 2010s further cemented Warhol's status as one of the most valuable artists in the world.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] In 2010, his work sold for a total of $313 million, accounting for 17% of all contemporary auction sales.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] In November 2013, Warhol's rarely exhibited diptych *Silver Car Crash (Double Disaster)* (1963) sold for $105.4 million at Sotheby's, setting a new auction record for the artist at the time.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] That same month, *Coca-Cola (3)* (1962) sold for $57.3 million at Christie's.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] In May 2014, *Race Riot* (1963), sold for $62.9 million and *White Marilyn* (1962), sold for $41 million at Christie's.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] Warhol's portrait of Marlon Brando, *Four Marlons* (1966), realized $69.6 million at Christie's in November 2014.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] In July 2015, Warhol's hand-painted canvas *One Dollar Bill (Silver Certificate)* (1962) fetched $32.8 million at Sotheby's.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] Warhol's market continued to expand globally into the 2020s.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] In March 2022, *Silver Liz (Ferus Type)* sold for ¥2.3 billion ($18.9 million) at Shinwa Auction, setting a new auction record in Japan.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] In May 2022, *Shot Sage Blue Marilyn* (1964) sold for $195 million at Christie's, becoming the most expensive American artwork ever sold at auction.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] Emily and Burton Tremaine were among Warhol's earliest collectors and most influential supporters.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] They acquired more than 15 of his works, including *Marilyn Diptych* (1962), now in the collection of Tate Modern in London, and *A Boy for Meg* (1962), now held by the National Gallery of Art in Washington, DC; both were purchased directly from Warhol's studio in 1962.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] In appreciation of their support and encouragement, Warhol once left a small *Head of Marilyn Monroe* at the Tremaines' New York apartment as a Christmas gift.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] Robert Scull and Ethel Scull were also early and significant patrons of Warhol's work.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] Ethel Scull became the subject of Warhol's first commissioned portrait, *Ethel Scull 36 Times* (1963), which is now part of the Metropolitan Museum of Art's collection.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] Warhol was an advocate of "Business Art", as he stated in his book *The Philosophy of Andy Warhol: From A to B and Back Again*: "I went into business art.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] I wanted to be an art business man or a business artist.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] Being good in business is the most fascinating kind of art," he said.
[src:false-color/andy-warhol-p02] His transformation into a mere business artist was a point of criticism.
